# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ballon-au-poing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The town was fought over during both World Wars, suffering significant damage, and was repeatedly occupied by both sides.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The 1918 Battle of Amiens was the opening phase of the Hundred Days Offensive which directly led to the Armistice with Germany.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The Royal Air Force heavily bombed the town during the Second World War.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] In the aftermath, the city was rebuilt according to Pierre Dufau's plans with wider streets to ease traffic congestion.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] These newer structures were primarily built of brick, concrete and white stone with slate roofs.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The architect Auguste Perret designed the Gare d'Amiens train station and nearby Tour Perret.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Amiens has an important historical and cultural heritage, on which a significant amount of tourism is based.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Apart from the cathedral, there are the hortillonnages, the Jules Verne House, the Tour Perret, the Musée de Picardie, the zoo, and the Saint-Leu and Saint-Maurice neighborhoods.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] A total of 60 monuments are listed in the inventory of monuments historiques, over 1600 places and monuments listed in the general inventory of cultural heritage, and 187 objects listed in the inventory of monuments historiques.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] During December, the town hosts the largest Christmas market in northern France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The first known settlement at this location was **Samarobriva** ("Somme bridge"), the central settlement of the Ambiani tribe, one of the principal tribes of Gaul.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The Romans named the town Ambianum, meaning settlement of the Ambiani people.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Amiens was part of Francia starting from the 5th century.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The Normans sacked the city in 859 and again in 882.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] In 1113, the city was recognized by King Louis VI of France, and in 1185 it was linked to the Crown of France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] In 1597, Spanish soldiers held the city during the six-month Siege of Amiens, before Henry IV regained control.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] During the 18th and 19th century, the textile tradition of Amiens became famous for its velours.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] As a result of the French Revolution, the provinces of France were dismantled and the territory was organised into departments.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Much of Picardy became the newly created department of Somme with Amiens as the departmental capital.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] During the industrial revolution, the city walls were demolished, opening up space for large boulevards around the town center.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The Henriville neighborhood in the south of the city was developed around this time.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] In 1848, the first railway arrived in Amiens, linking the city to Boulogne-sur-Mer.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] During the 1870 Battle of Amiens, the city was occupied by invading Prussian forces.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The town was fought over during both the First and Second World Wars, suffering significant damage and being occupied several times by both sides.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The 1918 Battle of Amiens was the opening phase of the Hundred Days Offensive which led directly to the Armistice with Germany that ended the war.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] In June 1944 following D-Day, Amiens was heavily bombed by the Royal Air Force.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The town was liberated by British forces on 31 August.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The city was rebuilt according to Pierre Dufau's plans with a focus on widening the streets to ease traffic congestion.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Amiens, once regional prefecture of the former Picardy Region, is the prefecture of the Somme department, one of the three departments (with Oise and Aisne) in the region.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Located in the Paris Basin, the city benefits from a privileged geographical position, with close proximity to Paris, Lille, Rouen, London and Brussels.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] At the crossroads of major European routes of travel (A1, A16 and A29), the city is also at the heart of a major rail star.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] As the crow flies, the city is 115 kilometres (71 mi) north of Paris, 97 kilometres (60 mi) south-west of Lille, 100 kilometres (62 mi) north-east of Rouen, 162 kilometres (101 mi) east-north-east of Le Havre and 144 kilometres (89 mi) north-west of Reims.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] At the regional level, Amiens is located 53 kilometres (33 mi) north of Beauvais, 71 kilometres (44 mi) west of Saint-Quentin, 66 kilometres (41 mi) from Compiègne and 102 kilometres (63 mi) from Laon.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] In area, Amiens is the third-largest settlement in the Somme, after Crécy-en-Ponthieu and Hornoy-le-Bourg.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The area of the commune is 4,946 hectares (12,220 acres); the altitude varies between 14 and 106 metres (46 and 348 ft).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The main stem of the River Somme passes through Amiens and is generally benign, except during exceptional floods that can last up to several weeks (such as in spring 2001).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] It is also, on its southeastern outskirts, close to Camon and Longueau, the confluence with its main tributary on the left bank (to the south), and the Avre.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The city developed in a natural narrowing of the river due to the advance of the rim of the Picard plateau in Saint-Pierre (ford crossing).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The Amiens citadel is built on this limestone butte of the Picard plateau and *Rue Saint-Pierre* is a slightly inclined path to leave the city from the north.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] At this narrowing, a network of narrow canals led to the construction of bridges and buildings including textile mills in the Middle Ages.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The marshes of the old bed of the river Somme was used to dig peat.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Farmers maintained rieux, canals and ditches by cleaning out the silt and used it to append to their vegetable garden plot.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] During the 20th century maintenance of the canals was stopped and gardens were gradually left to lie fallow or sold to private individuals who created pleasure gardens accessible by boat.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The hydrographic network has always been an important city-operated asset.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The river helped shape the identity of the landscape, urban and economic territory.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] It is around the Saint-Leu and Saint-Maurice neighborhoods that border the River Somme, as well as most of the administrative and civil area of the current city center which the city has developed since antiquity.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The Canal de la Somme dates from the beginning of the 19th century and the bridge at the foot of the citadel was built after World War II.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Amiens has the typical oceanic climate of the north of France, with relatively mild winters, cool summers, and rainfall well distributed throughout the year.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Amiens is a hub between the Île de France and the rest of northern France; Normandy and Benelux; and France and Great Britain.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Amiens is not directly on principal European road and rail arteries, such as the A1 motorway and the Paris-Lille TGV train line, at present.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] However, due to its position halfway between the urban areas of Lille and Paris, Amiens has good conditions for service and accessibility, including motorways (at the junction of the A16 and A29).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Amiens station is served by regional train services to destinations that include Rouen, Calais, Lille, Reims, Compiègne and Paris-Nord.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Saint-Roch (Somme) station in the western part of the city is served by local trains towards Rouen and Abbeville.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] A regular bus route with the TGV Haute-Picardie station also provides access to the Charles-de-Gaulle Airport station.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] On the horizon of 2025, the Roissy–Picardie Link will put Amiens 55 minutes from Paris Charles-de-Gaulle Airport and its TGV station.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Since antiquity, Amiens has been a crossroads of important routes.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The contemporary city is served by the A16 and A29 autoroutes.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The Jules Verne Viaduct, 943 metres (3,094 ft) long, crosses the River Somme to the east of the city and allows circumvention of the city by motorway-type roads.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The A16 and A29 autoroutes, the RN1 and the RN25 form a bypass-type motorway around the city that the population has called the *Rocade d'Amiens* or Amiens ring road.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] According to the urban transport plan (PDU) approved 19 December 2013 for the period 2013–2023 parking supply is considered abundant in Amiens.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Although important, demand for parking is less than what is available (capacity reserves are still 20% minimum: If the road is sometimes saturated, the occupancy rate of the underground parking remains globally less than 100%).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] In 2013, the city counted approximately 70,000 public parking spaces, including 8,400 in the city center and in its immediate vicinity, where 70% of places are paid.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] As of 2007, a residential parking system has been deployed in Saint-Anne ward to cope with congestion in the streets caused by SNCF railway station users.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] During the campaign for the municipal election of 2008, parking was one of the important topics of debate.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] A year after the change of majority, the Gilles Demailly team launched a consultation with the population.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] From 2011, residential parking was extended to the Gare-La-Vallée and Riolan neighborhoods, then in 2012 to the Noyon neighborhood and the area east of the Riolan sector.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] In 2014, 2,600 parking spaces were affected by this system which allowed city residents more parking near their homes in order to promote a better rotation of vehicles in the streets and reduce permanent occupation of public space by the cars cluttering the highway.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Amiens was once served by two tram lines with a combined length of 10.7 kilometres (6.6 mi), opened in 1887.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] They intersected at *Place Gambetta*, one linking La Madeleine Cemetery, the Church of Saint-Acheul, Cagnard bridge, *Rue de Noyon* and *Rue Jules-Barni*; the other from the Church of Saint-Pierre at the racecourse, by the streets of Saint-Leu, Frédéric-Petit and Colbert.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Electrified in 1899, the network grew to seven lines totaling 19 kilometres (12 mi) in 1906.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] From 1932, Longueau was linked to Amiens by a bus service.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] German bombing in 1940 destroyed most of the city center and hit the Jules-Ferry Road tram depot, totally destroying the tram fleet.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] A few old Parisian buses were also used in an extremely reduced service.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] These buses as well as the surviving bus were then converted to city gas and equipped with tanks on the roof covered by a huge white dome.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] This service continued until approximately 1946.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] There were only two urban lines: An east–west line (Saint-Acheul – Montieres) and a northeast–southwest line (Beauville – road to Rouen).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] It was decided after the war to serve the city by a trolleybus with one route to Longueau.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] This was only in part realized, serving Saint-Acheul, Rouen, La Madeleine and Saint-Pierre.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] In 1964, trolleybuses were abandoned and the bus became ubiquitous in Amiens transportation.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The current public transport network consists of a bus network managed by the Ametis mixed economy company, whose network covers Amiens Métropole, the agglomeration of Amiens.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The establishment of dedicated bus lanes began in 2006.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Former Mayor Gilles de Robien had envisioned the creation of a tram, but the choice of dedicated bus lanes had been preferred for reasons of cost and patronage.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] His successor, Mayor Gilles Demailly, had been considering the development of a TSCP in the metropolitan area.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] As a result of numerous studies and conferences, elected representatives voted for the creation of a tram at the municipal Council of 15 November 2012.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The project had been endorsed by the Communauté d'agglomération Amiens Métropole on 18 December 2012 and the commissioning of a first north–south tram route was scheduled for 2018/2019.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Improvement of public transit would then be only by that of the bus network.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Indeed, in December of the same year, the Community Council approved funding for a study (the sixth in 20 years) relating to the establishment of a rapid transit bus network (BHNS), which should enter into service in March 2019, and whose vehicles could be electric.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Amiens has developed two bike services: Buscyclette and Velam.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] In 2012, Amiens Métropole had 100 kilometres (62 mi) of routes for cyclists.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Despite the development of a bicycle plan in 1997 which was planning the development of 500 kilometres (310 mi) of equipped cycleways, the network of the territory in terms of paths is still incomplete.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The blueprint of the bicycle facilities of the agglomeration (SDAC) provides, over a period of 10 years (2014–2024), for 188 kilometres (117 mi) of cycle routes and equips 490 sites for the parking of bikes.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] This plan also includes the deployment of parking facilities over the entire territory of the city, close to the facilities frequented by bikers, as well as cyclist right-turns at traffic lights or even the maintenance of existing facilities.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Connections from these two stations include to Lille via Arras and Douai, to Boulogne via Abbeville, to Paris-Nord via Creil or Compiègne, to Reims via Tergnier, and to Rouen.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Many regional and extra regional links (Normandie, Grand Est and Île-de-France) pass through Amiens, especially by TER Hauts-de-France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] A station located 45 kilometres (28 mi) from Amiens, the Haute-Picardie TGV station, allows access to the TGV network.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Its isolated character earned it the name of *gare des betteraves*, or *gare betteraves*, at the time of its construction.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] In addition to Amiens – Glisy Aerodrome, bordering the town's eastern edge 5 kilometres (3.1 mi) from the center, there are several airports nearby.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The Somme canal runs through the town to the English Channel.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] This canal is linked to the Canal du Nord (Paris to Lille metropolitan area).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Amiens comprises a number of neighborhoods (French: *quartiers*) with their own characteristics, including Saint-Leu, St-Maurice, Henriville, and Saint-Acheul.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] St-Leu forms part of Amiens, north of the city center.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] It has many older wooden and brick houses and several canals.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] At the foot of the cathedral, traversed by canals, this picturesque area was largely rehabilitated during the 1990s.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] It extends to the Somme canal, located more to the north, at the foot of the Coteau Saint-Pierre on which the fortress of Jean Errard, called *Citadelle*, was built.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Historically, it was the poor neighborhood of the city, where butchers, tanners and dyers gathered.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Amiens University's Faculty of Sciences, present since the 1960s, has been renovated and expanded on occasion.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The Faculty of Law and Economics has also been transferred since the mid-1990s from the campus (offset to the south of the city) to its new location at the foot of the cathedral.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The open-air parking it replaces was a "gap" in the landscape dating from World War II.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Nonetheless, it allowed an unobstructed view of the cathedral.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Most of the buildings have been renovated and transformed into housing much of which is for students.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The area became the heart of the Amiens people's evenings, with many establishments (bars, restaurants, etc.) on *Place du Don* and *Quai Bélu*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The church is found at *Rue Saint-Leu*, located just between the Faculty of Science and Law-Economy (UPJV).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Two theatres were established in the neighborhood, that of the Chés Cabotans (puppet shows in the Picard language) and the *Maison du Théâtre* at the foot of the Saint-Leu Church.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] There is also *La Lune des Pirates*, a concert hall.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Located to the west of the Citadelle, and east of the La Madeleine Cemetery, this very old working-class neighborhood of Amiens acted as an industrial center in the 18th century.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] It is currently undergoing significant housing renovation and development.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Bordered by the Canal de la Somme, it offers a stopover for leisure boats, which must go through a lock.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The walls of the city's former dye factory are now those of the École supérieure d'art et de design d'Amiens (ESAD) as well as those of the Faculty of Arts.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The École supérieure d'ingénieurs en électronique et électrotechnique (ESIEE) is in the same neighborhood.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The Jardin des plantes, known as the *Jardin du Roy* within the city, is also located in this neighborhood.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The Henriville neighborhood was mostly built during the 19th century after the demolition of the city wall.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] It lies at the south of the town center.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] It has numerous bourgeois houses and townhouses, predominantly in brick, blending architectural styles of the period, including neoclassical, troubadour and neo-Gothic.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] There are also private mansions, such as the Acloque mansion and the house of Jules Verne.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The Saint-Acheul neighborhood (IPA: [sɛ̃t‿aʃœl]) existed before Amiens' inception, as people have lived there since prehistoric times.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] This is where archaeological excavations in the nineteenth century discovered prehistoric tool sets typical of the "Acheulean" prehistorical era, named after this neighborhood (also spelled Acheulian, pronounced [aʃœljɑ̃]).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Thr archaeological garden there is open to the public.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Not to be confused with the commune of Saint-Acheul situated 37 km (23 mi) to the north, the Saint-Acheul neighborhood is the site of a military cemetery from the First World War (1914–1918).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] It also contains the Church of Saint-Acheul, the Jesuit former Saint-Acheul College and the former normal school (teacher-training college), which became the Lycée Robert-de-Luzarches.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] A number of famous people are buried in the former Saint-Acheul cemetery, such as the creator of *Bécassine*, J.P.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Part of the neighborhood includes a so-called English neighborhood, with typical English-style houses.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] At the foot of this area lie the *hortillonnages*, a marshy area criss-crossed by canals.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] These areas experience a lot of social troubles and have regularly been the place for riots.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The cost of the latest vandalism to occur in the north of Amiens would amount, according to Gilles Demailly, to between four and six million euros.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] These extremely violent riots caused sixteen police officers to be injured.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] An extensive programme of redevelopment of these neighborhoods began recently, with demolition of HLM tower blocks and new infrastructure having been built, especially for schools.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] In 2009, the public transport network of the Amiens agglomeration was significantly modified.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] In 2017, the total number of dwellings in the municipality was 73,541, while it was 63,178 in 1999.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Among this housing, 88.7% were primary residences, 2.1% of secondary residences and 9.2% vacant housing.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] These dwellings were 35.6% of houses and 63.4% of apartments.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The proportion of principal residences, which were the properties of occupants, was 31.9%, down from 2007 (34.4%).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The share of empty rented HLM homes (social housing) was up: 29.8% against 29.4% in 2007, their number increased from 18,268 to 19,431.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] However, this percentage remains much greater than the rate of 20% required by the Law on Solidarity and Urban Renewal (SRU) for cities and agglomerations of more than 50,000 inhabitants.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The identity of the city is strongly marked by the specificity of its housing stock, consisting in a large proportion of detached houses, semi-detached, single or bourgeois: the *amiénoises*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] These traditional houses in the suburbs, in brick, were intrinsically linked to the expansion of the city during and after the Industrial Revolution.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The *amiénoise simple* includes a window on the ground floor and floors for attic and basement.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] It is built on a plot of a few metres wide but is very deep, and includes a garden, forming hearts with green islets and sparse areas.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The *amiénoise double* has two windows at each level.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The *grandes amiénoises* and townhouses rise to at least two floors with large rooms.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] They can have a gate opening onto a paved courtyard.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The official buildings or mansions regularly use brick façades on a sandstone base, decorated by stone window and door frames.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The Chanoines neighborhood has stone façades exclusively.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] In historic areas such as the Saint-Leu neighborhood, façades widely use wood, half-timbered or siding, and wattle and daub.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The toponym is derived from the name of the local Gallic people, the Ambiani, which in the 4th century, replaced the old name of the town Samarobriva (the bridge on the Samara – Somme).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Amiens then became the episcopal headquarters.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The Amiens municipal council has 55 elected members.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] On 4 April 2014, Brigitte Fouré (IDU (NC)) succeeded Gilles Demailly (PS) as mayor of Amiens.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Her list was elected in the second round on 30 March 2014 with 50.39% of the votes.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Amiens is a city marked by a strong judicial tradition, with the historical presence of its Court of Appeal, the Cour d'appel d'Amiens, as well as all courts of first and second degree of judicial order.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] The Court of Appeal of Amiens has jurisdiction over the three departments of Picardy, with nine high courts.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p01] Amiens also has friendly relations with Mianyang in China and Amiens in Australia.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The inhabitants of Amiens are called the *Amiénois* and their blason populaire is *Chés maqueux d'gueugues* (the eaters of nuts).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The population of Amiens has risen sharply since the mid-19th century: Its population doubled between 1850 and 1960, from 50,000 to 100,000 inhabitants, i.e. a gain of 50,000 people over this period of 110 years, and gaining about 30,000 others since (over 50 years only this time).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Amiens is distinguished by the youthfulness of its population.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Notably the age group 15-24 is much larger (21.2%) than the average of the Somme department (13.2%).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Educational institutions of the city fall under the supervision of the Academy of Amiens which develops curriculum according to the Inspection académique la Somme.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] On 1 September 2010, 10,658 children were enrolled in the Amiens public schools: 4,341 in nursery school and 6,317 in elementary school.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] In 2011, the Amiens agglomeration included 46 nursery schools, six elementary schools and 54 primary schools including eleven private.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] It had nine public colleges and six private colleges.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Amiens metropole welcomes one of the largest student populations in France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] In 2013, the city had 26,000 students (3,300 in short-term) and 800 researchers who are divided into some 40 institutions of higher education, 32 laboratories, and 10 units associated with the National Scientific Research Centre or the French Institute of Health and Medical Research.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Since 2014, the four sites have been gradually gathered on the current site of the South Hospital, with the exception of the long stay units for the elderly remaining in the Saint-Victor Centre.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] This merger will be completed in 2016 and allow the CHU of Amiens to increase its national and inter-regional dimension.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] This group represents the largest hospital construction of France and one of the most important in Europe with more than €630 million for work and equipment.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] At the end of the work, the total space of the CHU of Amiens will be 172,000 square metres (1,850,000 sq ft).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] It will total three blocks of hospitals with 400 beds each.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The CHU of Amiens is the largest employer in the Picardy region.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] At the end of the merger, there will be 6,700 employees, 1,300 students of the health professions, and 1,250 consultants who will go there each day.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] In order to maintain the availability of health units to the north of the city, a health center will open its doors in the first quarter of 2016, at the crossroads of the *Avenue de l'Europe* and the *Rue Maurice-Ravel*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] This health space of 1,200 square metres (13,000 sq ft) will host general practitioners and specialists of the CHU such as: cardiologist, a service of gynaecology-obstetrics, psychologists, dentist, and masseurs-physiotherapists.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] There is a promise of a permanence of care, 7 days a week and 24 hours a day.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Alongside the CHU, there are three private clinics, resulting from the consolidation of old clinics in the city.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] These care and hospitalisation institutions for medical, surgical, and obstetrics came together to create a private hospital center in the Vallée des Vignes neighborhood, south of the city.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The CHU of Amiens figured in 11th place in the *2013 awards of the hospitals and clinics* of the magazine *Le Point*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] In this ranking, the CHU stands out for ankle surgery (3rd), hip prosthesis (5th), foot surgery (7th) and paediatrics (14th).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] In this same classification, the Victor Palmer Health Group, equipped with a solid "mother-to-child hub", gained a 5th place in the table for the gynaecological clinics and an 8th place for breast cancers.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] In 2005, the CHU of Amiens became of international renown thanks to Professor Bernard Devauchelle, a native of the city, where his team performed the first partial face transplant in the world.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Thanks to a large proportion of youth in its population and the dynamism and the success of its sports clubs, Amiens has been awarded the title of "Sportiest city of France" by the *L'Équipe* newspaper in 1999.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The city had already won the title in 1969.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] In 2013, Amiens Métropole had nearly 300 sports associations and Sports Recreation: approximately 150 associations are grouped within the Office of Amiens Metropole Sports and 150 others are referenced without being adherents.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] According to this same Office for Sports, Amiens has 25,000 members of sports clubs, excluding school and university members.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Amiens Spartiates, operating in the top-level Ligue Élite de Football Américain, have been champions of France in 2004, 2010 and 2012.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Created in 1987, the club has more than 400 licensees.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Compagnie d'Arc d'Amiens is an archery club founded on 14 November 1803.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] AUC Athlétisme is a multidisciplinary athletic club which particularly developed Stella Akakpo, specialist of the sprint and the relay.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Bertrand Moulinet specialist of the 20 km and 50 km walk.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The AUC Badminton (Amiens University Badminton Club) was founded in 1986.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Labeled "French school of badminton" by the French Badminton Federation, the club had 205 members in 2014.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The city hosted the French National Badminton Championships in 2011.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Each 15 August at the Parc de la Hotoie, Amiens receives the final stages of Ballon au poing.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Circle of Fencing of Amiens Métropole is one of the oldest French clubs.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] It was succeeded in the Hall of arms of Amiens opened in 1886.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The circle has approximately 150 members and remains a major club of French fencing with many qualifications and results at the French Fencing Championships.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The club held the Elite French Championships in 2001 and 2011.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The team was finalist of the Coupe de France in 2001 and reached semifinals in 1930 and 2008, and played top-division Ligue 1 last time in 2020.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Its associated women's team is CS Amiens Club.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Before the 2012–2013 season, the team was known under the name of CS Amiens Montieres Etouvie.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] AC Amiens is the second biggest club in the city, currently playing in semi-professional Championnat National level.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Golf Club D'amiens was founded in 1924.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The men's team plays in D1, women team in D2.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Amiens Picardie Hand (APH), currently playing in National 2 (D4).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The club, a result of the merger of several Amiens clubs, was created in 1991.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Gothiques d'Amiens, currently playing in Ligue Magnus (D1), were champions of France in 1999 and 2004, and runners-up in France for 1989, 1997, 1998, 2003 and 2006.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The team plays at the Coliséum on the largest area of permanent ice in France (3800 seats).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Amiens hosted Division I of the 2006 Ice Hockey World Championships.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Amiens won the Championship of France in 6/6, 10 times.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Écureuils d'Amiens, Elite League (D1), were the runners-up of France in 2010, finalists of the Coupe de France in 2007 and finalists of the European Cup of clubs in 2008.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Sport Nautique d'Amiens (SNA) was founded in 1866.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Located on the edge of the Parc Saint-Pierre, it is labeled "French rowing school 3 stars" by the French Federation of rowing.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] With 465 members in 2013, the club currently competes in the 2nd division.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Rugby Club Amiénois (RCA) was founded in 1900.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The men's first team plays in Fédérale 3.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Amiens Métropole swim team, is that of Jérémy Stravius, who was a triple world champion of swimming and Olympic champion in the 4 × 100 m relay.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Amiens Sport Table Tennis (ASTT) was founded in 1945.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] It was twice crowned champion of France in 1968 and 1969.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The men's first team also won the Coupe de France in 1966 and 1967.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Amiens Athletic Club (AAC) was founded in 1904.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] It is one of the 10 biggest clubs in France with almost 1,000 members in 2013.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Amiens Longueau Métropole Volley-Ball (ALMVB) including women's first team plays in Women's Elite Division (D2) and the Amiens Métropole Volley-Ball (AMVB).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The men's first team plays in Nationale 1 (D3).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Amiens hosted the finish of Stage 8 of the 2018 Tour de France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] On 29 April 2006, Amiens hosted the French Federation of ice hockey created during the World Cup of Ice Hockey of Group B (antechamber of the world elite) organised in Amiens at the same time.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] It is now installed at Issy-les-Moulineaux.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Each 15 August at the *Parc de la Hotoie*, the city receives the final stages of the Picardy sports and in particular those of the most emblematic, traditional Picard sport: The Ballon au poing.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] This Picard game is played by teams of six.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] To be able to hit the ball, players surround their hand and their wrist with a strip of canvas or leather.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] From August 29 to September 1, 2012, the Compagnie d'Arc d'Amiens organizes the French FITA Archery Championships at the Hippodrome du petit Saint-Jean.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Free newspapers *Metro* and *20 minutes* are distributed in the city, including in Amiens railway station.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Since 7 February 1996, the Communauté d'agglomération Amiens Métropole distributes a free weekly local newspaper: JDA (*Journal des Amiénois*).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] This publication, which appears every Wednesday, is distributed to all homes in the metropolitan area and is made available in public places (taken at about 95,000 copies) as well as on the internet site of the city in its digital version.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Over time, the journal has evolved through various forms.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Carried out by the Directorate of communication of Amiens Métropole, the latest form dates to 16 January 2015.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] In addition to the JDA which is attached to information on the whole of the territory of Amiens Métropole, the city has also had monthly publications specific to the city, which no longer exist today: *Amiensville* then *Amiens Forum* (from April 2009 to June 2014).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The people of Amiens have other sources of information on their territory, such as the monthly publication of the Regional Council of Picardy, *Agir en Picardie*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Departmental Council of the Somme also sees its magazine distributed each month to the samariens homes, *Vivre en Somme*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Since 2006, the regional tourism committee of Picardy publishes *Esprit de Picardie*, a travel magazine on the Picardy region, every six months.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Most of the national radio stations broadcast their programs in the Amiens area and can be added to France Bleu Picardie (100.2 MHz) and local stations Radio Campus Amiens (87.7 MHz) and Radio Galaxie programme Évasion (97.7 MHz).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] As of 1 March 2015, the CSA has not selected Amiens for broadcast or experimentation of this broadcasting standard.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Zen Sōtō Zen centre affiliated with the international Zen Association, on *Rue Vulfran Warmé*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The synagogue in Amiens is located at 12 *Rue du Port d'Amont*, near Pont-Beauville.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has a place of worship on the Doullens road.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The city of Amiens has the largest Muslim community of Picardy and one of the largest in the north of France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Places of worship are evolving, several mosques are in a phase of expansion or relocation.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Several independent prayer rooms are present in the urban community.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] On the other hand, Muslim committees and associations exist in the image of the Islamic Cultural Centre of Amiens in the *Rue de Savoie*, the Muslim Cultural Freedom Association – Institute of Enlightenment and also the Association of residents of the home at 21 *Route d'Allonville*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Protestant Church of Amiens, *Rue Saint-Jacques*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] As both an industrial hub and a services center, Amiens enjoys a large pool of workers with a labor pool of over 350,000 inhabitants and numerous professional training courses.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The magazine *L'Entreprise* elected Amiens "Most attractive city of France" for businesses, in 2009 and 2007, for the category less than 200,000 inhabitants.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The strengths of the city include a developed real estate business and taxation around the average for French cities.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] In addition, its geographical position in the center of the triangle "Paris – London – Brussels", is between three major European cities.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The magazine *Challenges* has also designated Amiens as "Best managed city of France", for the category large cities with more than 100,000 inhabitants, in 2011, 2010 and 2008.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] In 2010, the median taxable household income was €22,539, which placed Amiens at 177th place among the 31,525 communes with more than 39 households in metropolitan France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] In 2017, the proportion of taxable households was 45%.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] In 2017, the population aged 15 to 64 years amounted to 91,555 persons, among which there were 64.5% of assets including 51.4% having a job and 13.1% of unemployed.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] There were 78,284 jobs in the employment area, against 80,908 in 2007.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The number of assets employed and residing in the area of employment being 47,588.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The concentration of jobs indicator is 164.5%, which means that the employment area offers three jobs for every two active inhabitants.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Agriculture has very little representation among Amiens jobs with only 0.2%, just as the construction sector which represents 4.3% of jobs.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Unlike these two sectors whose share is below the national average, the tertiary sector (trade, transport, services) represents a significant part of the Amiens workforce, 42.3%.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Public services (public administration, education, health, social work) accounts for 42.7%.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company announced more than 400 job cuts in May 2008 at the Amiens plant, which has had 1,450 employees; in March 2009, the management announced new collective redundancies of a thousand jobs.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] On 31 December 2015, at Amiens, there were 10,436 businesses: 51 in agriculture, forestry and fisheries, 394 in industry, 685 in construction, 7,110 in trade, transportation and various services and 2,196 were related to the administrative sector.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] In 2018, 1,505 companies had been recorded as being established in Amiens, including 1,206 companies owned by sole proprietors.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Philatelic publishers Yvert et Tellier (catalogues of quotes) and *l'Écho de la timbrologie* (magazine) have their management in Amiens, even if they have more of their services in the Paris region.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Gueudet Group, one of the largest car dealers in France, was established at Amiens in 1918.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The old textile tradition of the city remains with the factory of Lee Cooper France (122 employees).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Since the end of World War II, much of the city's economy was tied to automotive equipment with companies such as Valeo, Goodyear and Sumitomo-Dunlop tires.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] In 2003, the American Goodyear company bought Dunlop.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] These two companies suffered financially through late 2007 and early 2008, and in response, the American Goodyear company headquarters in the United States offered workers a change to their working hours and the number of posts, which a high percentage of staff refused.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Procter & Gamble, settled in Amiens in 1964 to produce soap, and inaugurated its new detergents unit in 1966.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Established on over more than 45 hectares (110 acres), it is one of the largest factories in the world for laundry cleaning products (Ariel, Dash, Bonux, Gama) and for domestic cleaning products (Mr.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] More than 85% of its production is intended for export.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Amiens plant employs approximately 930 people.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Since the mid-1990s, the city has tried to convert the economy towards the internet and telephony industries.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Many call centres (Intracall center, Coriolis France, Médiamétrie) have opened mainly within the city, region or state.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] The Unilog (now Logica) computer service company has installed a service center in Amiens (the CSA).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] Amiens is the seat of the Regional Chamber of commerce and industry of Picardy.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] It is also the seat of the Chamber of commerce and industry of Amiens.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p02] It manages the Amiens - Glisy Aerodrome.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The strategic position of Amiens makes it an attractive destination for a weekend or a few days, from Paris, Lille or Brussels.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Amiens also benefits from the proximity of the Baie de Somme, a tourist hotspot registered at the Club des plus belles baies du monde and labelled Great Site of France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Amiens has the label of Towns and Lands of Art and History since 1992.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Within this framework, the host of the heritage organises guided tours on themes intended for an audience of adults and children, with educational workshops.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] A signposted circuit allows an independent tour of the town, with information panels offering comment on places and notable buildings.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Amiens has an important historical and cultural heritage, and an accessible and varied natural heritage, on which tourism is based.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The main attractions are the cathedral, which is included in the world heritage of UNESCO, the *hortillonnages*, Jules Verne House, the Tour Perret, the Musée de Picardie, the zoo, and the Saint-Leu and Saint-Maurice neighborhoods.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The information given below is relative only to a brief selection.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The city is famous for its Notre-Dame Cathedral, masterpiece of Gothic art and one of the largest cathedrals in the world by its interior volume (200,000 m3 (7,100,000 cu ft)).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The largest religious and medieval building of France, its interior could twice hold Notre-Dame de Paris.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The cathedral measures 145 metres (476 ft) long and its spire rises 112 metres (367 ft) high.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The vaults of the central nave, finished in 1247, are 42.3 metres (139 ft), close to the maximum limit for this architecture.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Dating back to the 13th century, its construction is due to the wealth of the city in the Middle Ages and to the fire of the Romanesque cathedral which stood previously.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Three architects, including Robert of Luzarches succeeded to complete the construction.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Amiens Cathedral is notable for the coherence of its plan, the beauty of its three-tier interior elevation, the particularly fine display of sculptures on the principal façade and in the south transept, and inlays of its floor.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Regarded as the archetype of the classic Gothic style, the cathedral also presents some elements of the radiant Gothic style and flamboyant Gothic.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The speed of construction, barely 70 years for the shell (1220 to 1269), explains this remarkable homogeneity of style.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Its façade is decorated with more than 3,000 statues, gargoyles and chimeras.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Registered since 1981 as a World Heritage Site of UNESCO, it is a "masterpiece of world heritage".
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] For a second time in 1998, it is a monumental step on the Camino de Santiago.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Despite the two World Wars of the 20th century, which severely affected the city, it managed to stay intact.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] A show of the reproduction of the original polychromy of façades, discovered as a result of recent laser cleaning, is given annually for free in December and during the summer period.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The show is a projection on the façade of slides in color.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The zodiac is a set of reliefs on the foundations of the western façade formed series of quatrefoil medallions, carved in a representative agrarian calendar and the signs of the zodiac.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The statue of the weeping Angel that is on a tomb carved by Nicolas Blasset, and the reliefs evoking Saint-Firmin and St.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] John the Baptist, are some of the well-known works of the cathedral.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] At ground level lies the intact labyrinth of 234 metres (768 ft) long.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] On the north side of the cathedral is the former Palace of the Bishop of Amiens, occupied by the École supérieure de commerce in Amiens.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The origin of the Belfry of Amiens dates back to the establishment of the commune of Amiens by Louis VI.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] It is mentioned for the first time in an arbitral award issued by the chapter of Amiens in 1244.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Symbolizing the independence of the commune, it was formerly used for meetings of the notables of the city and then as archive rooms, weapons store and prison.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] A spotter nearby monitored arrivals and warned the population of the external dangers.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] During the Middle Ages, the building was repeatedly engulfed by fire.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The belfry is composed of a base in white cut stone, built in the 15th century between 1406 and 1410, a stone superstructure bell tower built from 1749 with Baroque volutes at its base, and a dome covered with slate and then the renowned arrow weather vane.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] At the time, a huge 11-ton bell was installed inside, it was later destroyed along with the dome, whose copper component melted, in the bombardment and fire of the city on 19 May 1940.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Abandoned and devoid of a roof since World War II, the monument was fully restored between February 1989 and July 1990.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Located on the *Place au Fil*, the old central square of the city before the arrival of the railway and the rise of the *Rue des Trois Calloux*, the belfry is adjacent to *Les Halles* and the back of the *Hôtel de Ville* (city hall).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] At a height of 52 metres (171 ft), it rings every hour of the day.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Since July 2005, the belfry of Amiens is a UNESCO World Heritage Site, as part of a set of 56 Belfries of Belgium and France which were inscribed because of their architecture and their importance in the rise of municipal power in Northern France and Belgium.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The belfry is also recorded in the inventory of Historic Monuments.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] In 1845, the traditional fair of Saint-Jean, formerly held at *Place René Goblet*, was transferred to *Place Longueville*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] It is a wide esplanade that took the place of the Longueville bastion, after the demolition of the city walls in the early 19th century.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Each year, a temporary circus is established for this occasion.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] In 1865, a circus company emerged to claim a permanent circus, which would be built in wood by the Schytte contractor in 1874.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] However, expensive maintenance prompted the municipality to consider the construction of a new building.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The decision was made in 1886 under the leadership of Mayor Frédéric Petit and the work began.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The Chief Architect of the Somme, Émile Ricquier, a disciple of Gustave Eiffel, was responsible for its construction.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] It was inspired by the Cirque d'hiver of Paris but with a cast metal frame, supplemented by brick from the local countryside.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The architect of civil buildings, Charles Garnier, claimed that the frames should be hidden with a plaster imitating stone.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The "moderninst" design of Ricquier, who chose to display the structure, and to favor local material such as brick, is visible at the rear of the monument.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] With its 16-sided polygonal shape and a diameter of 44 metres (144 ft), it includes lodges and stalls in its enclosure.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] As a completely modern project, it hosted two steam engines, dedicated to fully electric lights and central heating.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Since its construction, it was also the first circus which included a buffet and a refreshment bar.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The cost of the construction of the building finally reached double the forecast.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The roof was damaged by a shell in 1916.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The circus was the setting for Federico Fellini's *The Clowns* (1971), and the film by Jean-Jacques Beineix, *Roselyne and the Lions* (1989), with Isabelle Pasco as lead actress.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The largest of the circuses of the province with its 3,000-seats, the building has acquired a multidisciplinary use for decades of performances of theatre, dance, concerts, galas, sports and public meetings.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Renovated in 2003, it now bears the name of Cirque Jules-Verne.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] After hosting the performances of Cirque Rancy, it hosts resident Cirque Arlette Gruss.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Since 1 January 2011, the circus has been labelled "national hub circus and street arts", managed by an EPCC.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] It is one of seven in France and is still in use today.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] In 1882, Jules Verne and his wife, Honorine, rented the house at the corner of *Rue Charles-Dubois* and *Boulevard Longueville* until 1900.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Acquired in 1980 by the city, the house is labeled Maisons des Illustres by the Ministry of Culture.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Restored in 2006, thanks to the work of the Centre international Jules-Verne, this 19th-century mansion, registered as a national heritage site, traces through the exhibition of more than 700 objects, the personality, the sources of inspiration and memories of Jules Verne.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Opposite the Gare d'Amiens, is located the Tour Perret (from the name of its architect Auguste Perret).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Over 100 metres (330 ft) high, it was one of the first skyscrapers built in Europe, and the highest for a long time.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The Église Saint-Leu d'Amiens was built at the end of the 15th century, on the model of the hall-churches.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] It is dedicated, as its district, to Saint Leu, referring to the 7th century bishop who was exiled to the Vimeu.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] A flamboyant portal adorns the base of the steeple.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The latter, struck by lightning, had to be rebuilt at the beginning of the 16th century.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Stone and wood statues date from the 17th century.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The choir houses the glory of the Duthoit brothers.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Amiens has 270 hectares (670 acres) of green space (excluding communal woodland) 118,300 hectares (292,000 acres) of *hortillonnages*, 300 hectares (740 acres) of forests, 30 hectares (74 acres) of marshland, in addition to its river and its streams.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Floral City awarded the maximum score of 4 flowers in the floral contest of cities and villages of France to Amiens, and it offers a particularly rich wooded heritage.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] With 38,650 trees (excluding woodland), of which 17,000 are situated on highways, Amiens to win the national tree award.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] In 2014, the city ranked in the top 10 greenest cities of France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Presenting itself as a city concerned with the environment, Amiens has made the link between the city and nature a central axis of its metropolitan development project called *Amiens 2030*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Amiens is also known for the hortillonnages, gardens on small islands in over 300 hectares (740 acres) of marshland between the River Somme and River Avre, surrounded by a grid network of human-made canals (locally known as "rieux").
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] They are also known as the "floating gardens of Amiens".
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The *hortillonnages* are sometimes called "Little Venice of the North", because of the canals.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Prior to its opening in May 1952, the Amiens Zoo is a green space bordering the basin of the Park of the Hotoie.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] It was the mayor of the time, Maurice Vast, who decided to develop the site in 1949.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Originally intended as an entertainment venue, the zoo began its mission of conservation, education and research between 1970 and 1980.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Between 1990 and 2000, the zoo was completely renovated and became a permanent member of the European Association of Zoos and Aquaria (EAZA) in 2001 and the National Association of Zoological Parks (ANPZ) in 2002.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Today, there are 300 animals, representing approximately 75 species from all continents, cohabiting on 6.5 hectares (16 acres).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] They live in environments, which are close to their natural environment, favouring their well-being.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Traditionally, entry is free on 14 July, Bastille Day.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Parc du Grand Marais, along the Somme Canal, to the west of the city.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Covering over 25 hectares (62 acres), this park has many sports facilities: American football stadium, skate bowl, football field, play structures.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Jardin des plantes originally called the *Jardin du Roy*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] Created in 1751, it is the oldest garden of Amiens on the *Boulevard du jardin des plantes*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] As a floral city, 4 flowers were awarded in 2013 by the National Council of Cities and Villages of France for the competition of floral cities and villages.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p03] The national Council of Cities and Villages awarded the 2012 National Tree Prize to the city for "its exceptional and innovative management of its wooded heritage" with its 37,000 trees, some more than a century old.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] Amiens was strongly tipped to host the Louvre II.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] The city has a number of concert spaces, mostly small venues, and pubs also host numerous concerts throughout the year.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] Amiens Métropole has nine cultural centers which cover much of the metropolitan area: six in various districts of Amiens, and three in the neighbouring communes of Longueau, Camon and Glisy.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] These outreach facilities working in the field of art and creation are openly oriented "venues".
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] Open to all, they offer an eclectic programme; theatre and concerts, shows for young people and dance, projections of films, exhibitions, meetings and debates.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] The Bibliothèques d'Amiens Métropole is a network of 28 facilities spread over the whole territory of the metropolis.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] The heart of this network is the Louis Aragon library, located on *Rue de la République*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] Built between 1823 and 1826, it is one of the oldest municipal libraries in France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] It experienced several improvements, including campaigns of work between 1982 and 1993, which have endowed it with new spaces: Two auditoriums, a youth space, a library and an art library.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] Registration and borrowing is free for all of the people of Amiens in all libraries.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] Two libraries also provide service to neighborhoods and the communes of the agglomeration, and there is home delivery of documents for people with reduced mobility.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] Throughout the year, Amiens is the seat of many cultural, traditional or economic events.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] Even if it rarely achieves national notoriety (with the notable exceptions of Les Fatals Picards, The Rabeats, Olympe, Albin de la Simone, Disiz and Rokia Traoré), the Amiens music scene is active and developed.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] In this dynamic, the New French Rock scene holds a central place and is organised around a collective, *Amiens Burning*, which is responsible for networking the breeding ground for the local rock scene, to accompany its projects, and organize concerts.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] Since their creation, La Lune des Pirates and Cité Carter also provide support to the local scene.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] For example, the Cité Carter produces a compilation each year, with local groups.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] Classical music is represented by the Orchestre de Picardie and the University Orchestra of Picardy.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] Vocal practice is represented by the Regional Choir of Picardy, the University Choir of Picardie, and the Choir of France Picardy.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] One can also include the Harmony Saint-Pierre, a fanfare of 70 musicians, which has become a local institution since its inception in 1894.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] The city has the Conservatoire à rayonnement régional d'Amiens, seat of strong musical activity (framed by 70 teachers, an administrative and technical team with an additional 20 people).
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] Amiens saw rise, over the centuries, to major writers.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] In the first half of the 17th century, Vincent Voiture, poet and letter writer, was the darling of the Précieuses for the fluidity of his style.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] In 1634, he was member of the 1st Académie française.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] In 1678, Charles du Fresne, sieur du Cange, nicknamed "the French Varro", published his *Glossarium* in 3 volumes.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] This glossary of medieval Latin is still authoritative today.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] In 1750, Jean Baptiste Gresset, a playwright and poet who was celebrated in his time and was a member of the Académie française, founded the Academy of Amiens which is still active today.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] In 1782, the Amiens native Choderlos de Laclos published *Les Liaisons dangereuses* where he staged a depraved nobility.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] Considered one of the masterpieces of 18th-century literature, the book has toured the world and is known as an Oscar-winning film adaptation.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] In the 19th century, there was a brilliant literary life around the Académie des sciences, des lettres et des arts d'Amiens with historian Albéric de Calonne and the Yvert family.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] However, the great name of Amiens literary life is Jules Verne.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] He animated all intellectual activity, giving balls and parties, while his wife held a famous salon.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] He often attended the library of the industrial society, which subscribed to numerous scientific journals.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] Engaged in local life, he was Councillor of Amiens from 1888 to 1904.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] He was closely interested in the affairs of the city, wrote many reports on the theatre and brought its support to the construction of the municipal circus.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] Amiens does appear explicitly in his novels but there are however characteristic elements of the city such as the cathedral and the river.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] This is the case, for example, for the imaginary city of Ragz in *Le secret de Wilhem Storitz*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] In the novel *Une fantaisie du docteur Ox*, the inhabitants of the fictional town of Virgamen, the Virgamenois, refer directly to the Amiénois and their prudent nature.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] In 1875, he delivered before the Academy of Sciences, Letters and Arts of Amiens a speech entitled "An ideal city: Amiens in the year 2000" where he portrays himself wandering in a forward-thinking city of Amiens.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p04] Since then, the city has built a tourist route from this text.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] He died in Amiens in 1905, and he deeply marked the town's footprint, so that today many places, monuments and events bear his name.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] He rests at La Madeleine cemetery where one can read on his tomb: *Vers l'immortalité et l'éternelle jeunesse.* [Towards immortality and eternal youth].
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] In 1885, Englishman John Ruskin published the Bible of Amiens, which was translated into French, extensively annotated and prefaced, in 1904, by Marcel Proust.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] This book dedicated to Notre-Dame d'Amiens was the opportunity for Proust to recall his admiration for the English author and the Cathedral of Amiens.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] In the second half of the 19th century, Jules Barni, Member of Parliament for the Somme, Associate Professor of philosophy and brilliant scholar translated Kant's work in French and thus enabled its dissemination in France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] A native of Amiens, Paul Bourget published *Le Disciple* in 1889, a novel today considered his major work.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] He was elected, 5 years later, to the Académie française.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] Born in Sainte-Anne district in 1885, Roland Dorgelès published *Les Croix de bois* in 1919.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] A masterpiece written from his notes taken at the Front, the novel won the Prix Femina the same year.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] Though capable of obtaining the Prix Goncourt, it was beaten by À l'ombre des jeunes filles en fleurs by Marcel Proust, 6 votes against 4.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] A member of the Académie Goncourt in 1929, he was elected president in 1954 until his death in 1973.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] In 1926, the Amiens native Henri Deberly, won the Prix Goncourt with Le Supplice de Phèdre, a novel inspired by his home city.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] Many films or scenes from films were shot in Amiens and its surroundings.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] Amiens is a stronghold of comics in France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] A whole generation of designers and Amiens writers make the city an important creative center of the 9th art.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] The main actors in this generation, include Régis Hautière, Norédine Allam who notably led the recolouring of the 33 Asterix albums in the framework of the project "The great collection" and also Antoine Dodé, David François, Fraco, Hardoc, Greg Blondin, and Nicolas Hitori De.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] The city was also the birthplace or home of big names in the comic strip universe, such as the Amiens native Joseph Pinchon, creator of the character of *Bécassine*; Paul Gillon, winner of the Grand Prix de la ville d'Angoulême and also Philippe Thirault.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] Actor of this dynamic around the BD, the association *On a marché sur la bulle* [Explorers on the bubble] organises the Rendez-vous de la bande dessinée d'Amiens, one of the greatest French comic book festivals.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] Active throughout the territory, the structure also manages a resource center and has an editorial department with the Éditions de la Gouttière.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] Amiens, in the image of the Picardy region, has a rich gastronomic heritage.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] The region is also known for "flamiche aux poireaux", a puff pastry tart made with leeks and cream.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] The Summer Rambo apple cultivar originated near Amiens in the 16th century.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] Marie Denizard (1872-1959), in January 1913, the first woman to stand as a candidate in a French presidential election.
[src:ballon-au-poing/amiens-p05] In 1991, the municipality formed around Gilles de Robien designed a new logo, incorporating the Fleur-de-lis and the Ivy leaf present on the coat of arms, placed side by side in red with a background of grey or white, depending on usage.
[src:ballon-au-poing/balle-à-la-main] The ball is made with a lead pit, surrounded with wool and covered with leather.
[src:ballon-au-poing/balle-à-la-main] The diameter is about 4,2 cm with a weight about 43 g.
[src:ballon-au-poing/balle-à-la-main] The game takes place according to the rules of the games of *gagne-terrain* (gain-ground) with in particular the use of the "*chasses*".
[src:ballon-au-poing/balle-à-la-main] Points for a set count by "fifteen" (15, 30, 45 and set), with possible advantage in the tie-break.
[src:ballon-au-poing/ballon-au-poing] The **ballon au poing** is a popular team sport in Picardy (France).
[src:ballon-au-poing/ballon-au-poing] This sport must not be confused with the fistball.
[src:ballon-au-poing/ballon-au-poing] The teams are separated on the ground by a line (*la corde* - the rope) which is mobile during the party.
[src:ballon-au-poing/ballon-au-poing] The purpose of the game is to gain ground by moving the rope.
[src:ballon-au-poing/ballon-au-poing] To do it, we try to make the ball "*die*" in the opposite camp.
[src:ballon-au-poing/ballon-au-poing] Each 15 August at the Parc de la Hotoie (Amiens), the city receives the final stages of Ballon au poing.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] When fistball was invented is unknown, but its roots probably lie in Southern Europe, or more specifically, Italy.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The earliest known written mention of the game is by Roman Emperor Gordian III from 240 AD.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Rules for an Italian version of fistball were recorded by Antonio Scaino in 1555.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In the 16th century, the game experienced a renaissance, although it was mostly regarded as a pastime for nobles and gentry.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In 1786, Johann Wolfgang von Goethe mentioned fistball games between "four noblemen from Verona and four Venetians" in his diary *An Italian Journey*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] It was only in 1870 that fistball was introduced to Germany, led by Georg Weber.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The sport was mainly played by gymnasts and was therefore regarded as a gymnastic sport.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Fistball was first presented to the public in 1885 at the German Gymnastics Festival in Dresden.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In 1894, Georg Weber, along with Heinrich Schnell, drafted the first rules that outlined a competitive and organised sport.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The play and scoring however differed significantly from fistball as it is known today.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Subsequently, the sport spread to surrounding, mainly German-speaking, countries, and German emigrants also brought the sport to all continents, particularly in South America and West Africa.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Fistball was first introduced to the United States in 1911 by high school teacher Christopher Carlton who had experienced it on holiday in Italy.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] At the 1913 German Gymnastics Festival in Leipzig, the first German men's championships were held, where LLB Frankfurt won against 1879 MTV Munich, winning 114:101.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Due to the First World War, no German Championships were held between 1914 and 1920.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In 1921, the first women's fistball championship was held, with Hamburger Turnerschaft defeating TV Krefeld by 91:90.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Fistball, while still a game affiliated to the Gymnastics Association, began to grow independently.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In 1927, almost 12,000 teams played organised fistball in Germany.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Due to the rapid spread of the fistball game and improved game skills, further changes in the rules were necessary, with a greater focus on winning points through forcing errors.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] This style of play was more athletic and dynamic, and tactics began to change significantly.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The development of fistball was halted by the Second World War.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In order to encourage development and improve performance, the International Fistball Association (IFA) was founded in 1960, which is the umbrella organization of all national fistball organizations worldwide.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The first IFAF World Championships for men were held in Linz, Austria in 1968, with West Germany winning gold.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The first IFA World Championships for women were held in Buenos Aires, Argentina in 1994, with Germany winning gold.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Both tournaments are currently held quadrennially.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] A relative latecomer to fistball, Australia established their own fistball federation in 2013 and host a national league, the Victorian Fistball League, notably including Melbourne Thunder and Fist Club.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] South Africa followed a year later in also establishing their own federation.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Fistball is a team sport in which two teams compete against each other on two half-fields, similar to volleyball.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] They are separated by a center line and a net stretched between two posts up to two meters in height.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] If the net or posts are touched by either a player or the ball during play, this is considered an error.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Each team consists of five players, with players trying to play the ball across the net from one half of the field of play to the opponents' half – using only their arm or closed fist (unlike in volleyball where open hands are allowed) – in a way in which the opponents cannot return it.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] After clearing the net, the ball may be contacted up to three times by the five players on each team – with a bounce being permissible before each contact (also unlike in volleyball where no bounce is allowed), but no repeat hits by any individual player within the three attempts.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Similar to volleyball, the three hits are ideally used to save, set and spike the ball back into the opponents half, in that order.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] If a team cannot return the ball or makes an error, the other team gets a point.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The team that lost the last point or committed the last error makes the next service.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] A set ends when one team has scored 11 points and is at least 2 points in the lead (i.e. at least 11:9).
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] If the score reaches 10:10, play will be extended automatically until one of the teams takes the lead by 2, or is the first to win 15 points (scores may therefore end 15–14).
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The number of winning sets varies depending on the game class, but is generally played to best of five or three.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In some cases, set results are limited by time, and this can be common in large tournaments for organizational purposes.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In summer (field season), it is played outside on a grass or turf sports field (field size 50 x 20 m).
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In winter (indoor season) is played in an indoor sports hall, and generally an already existing handball court is used as a playing field (field size 40 x 20 m).
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In the hall, the ball has a more controlled bounce than on grass, which has an effect on the game tactics.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In addition, in the hall, any wall contact by the ball is an error.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In outdoor fistball, the field size is 50 m long by 20 m wide (25 x 20 m per half-field).
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In indoor fistball, the field size is 40 m long by 20 m wide (20 x 20 m per half-field).
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Since the indoor field size corresponds with the regular size of a handball field, the existing external lines are usually used.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The service line is 3 m away from the center line.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The server's stationery foot (for standing serves) or first landing foot (for jumping serves) must be completely behind this line when serving.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The boundary lines belong to the field, i.e. when the ball touches the line, this is not an error and play will continue.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The playing field is divided in half by a 5 cm wide ribbon-like red and white net.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] It is held above the center line between two posts, its upper edge is located at 2 m height (men) and 1.90 m (women).
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] For the D-Youth (under 12), the height is 1.60 m, the C-youth (under 14 years) 1.80 m.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The field also includes a run-off area, which when playing outdoors is 8 m to the rear and 6 m on the sides.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] For indoor play, run-off areas are limited by the wall or stands, but are generally a minimum of 1 m to the rear and 0.5 m at the sides.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The field dimensions given are for adult players, as youth fields are generally smaller.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] A standard fistball is hollow, filled with air and is made of leather.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] It must be inflated evenly until it is round and taut.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] For indoor fistball games, and for different weather conditions in outdoor fistball games, players can use trade association-approved balls with different surfaces (for example, natural leather, plastic coating, rubberized surface).
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The weight of a ball can vary between 320 and 350 g (females) and 350-380 g (males).
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Its scope must be 65–68 cm, and its air pressure from 0.55 to 0.75 bar.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] It is thus as hard as a soccer ball (0.6-0.7 bar) and harder than a volleyball (0.29 to 0.32 bar).
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In physical size, it is similar to a football or a volleyball.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The right to select the game ball is determined by lot before the game and replaced after each set.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Increasingly, uniform balls are outlined and provided by the organizers to ensure equal opportunity for all teams participating at international championships.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The ball can often be spiked at speeds of up to 100–120 km / h.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In the field of youth other ball dimensions come (especially lower weights) are used, see the regulations.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In contrast to volleyball, where the players rotate and assume a different position after each change of service, in fistball each player has a fixed position.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] While players can rotate into different positions during a game, this is rather unusual, as each player is a specialist in their position.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Another difference from volleyball is that a fistball playing field is much larger, and fistball teams have fewer players on the field at one time than volleyball teams, and therefore fistball players are required to cover much more space during play.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The main reason for these differences is because the ball can bounce once between each player's hit, resulting in differing strategies to volleyball.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Depending on playing conditions (hardwood or grass, wet ground etc.), formations can change.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] At international levels, outdoor fistball is also played in the U-shape, mainly due to the better defenses that it can provide against fast and powerful attacking shots.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The players playing at this level are required to have significant speed and fitness in order to cover the ground for both defending and attacking hits.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Another formation option, although rare, is the V-shape.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] This is generally used when playing on wet grass.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In this case the setter stands behind the baseline and the two defensive players move diagonally inwards to form a V shape.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] As an attacking shot hit on wet grass tends to slip more and bounce less, this formation gives teams more chance to get underneath the bounce of the ball to hit it upward in return.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Substitutions may be anywhere at any position field, but only before that team is about to serve, during a time out, between sets, or whenever the referee has stopped play.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Force, accuracy and fluid sequence of body movements are necessary to make full effect of the service.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] With a service, the server will attempt to achieve a direct point with it via an "ace", or will at least hope to force the opponent into a difficult first hit, thereby affecting the buildup of the opponent's return hit.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The ball is hit mostly with the inner surface of the fist, due to control.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] However, if the server wishes to hit the ball with full force, they will use the edge of a clenched hand.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] This is called a "hammer hit", and carries greater risk of failure due to the smaller impact surface than the inner surface of the fist.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The server will attempt to hit the ball into an area on the opposition's side of the field that will be difficult for the opposition to return.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] For example, this can be done by hitting the ball long to the back line, directly at the feet of an opposition player, diagonally across the court, or with a short ball just over the net.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] A difficult, yet highly effective variation to the serve is to add curve to the hit.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] This can be done by sweeping across the ball from left to right, or vice versa, when hitting with the inside surface of the fist.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] If done correctly, the ball should appear to curve away from or into the opposition, confusing their return.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] When preparing to serve, the server must stand behind the service line (3-meter line).
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Upon completion of the service hit, the server's first contact with the ground must be behind the service line.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] For example, if the server jumps while serving, the first foot to touch the ground upon landing must be behind the line.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The second foot may then land in front of the line.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] This same rule applies for standing serves.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] If this is not correctly complete, the server will be charged with a fault, and the opposition will receive a point.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In addition, the ball must visibly leave the hand prior to hitting (i.e. it must be thrown).
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] It must not be pushed away out of the holding hand in an attempt to surprise the opponent, as this will also count as an error.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The defender must be skillful in order to ensure their team can launch an effective attack.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] If a defensive shot is returned ineffectively, there will be little chance for a strong attack.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The ball from an opponent's strong attacking hit or serve can be very hard to return, and most successful defenses are the result of running hard for the return.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Players will often be required to jump or dive in order to reach the ball even before it hits the ground for the second time.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] A good defense is performed using the inside of the forearm while positioned behind the ball, facing the net.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] If the inside of the forearm not exactly behind the ball, the ball will not go in the desired direction, and will instead go erratically sideways.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] This is especially the case when the ball is wet.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In order to lower the physical impact of the hit, one can retract the arm at the moment of impact, but this can be difficult.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] A good defender possesses agility, speed, responsiveness, technical ability, positional sense and courage to put in physical effort to make contact.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Commitment of each player makes up the foundation of the fistball sport dynamic.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The setter substantially affects the nature of the following attack.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The setter must be able to position the ball in the air and on the field in a place that an attack can effectively take place.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] This hit may need to take place from anywhere on the field, including the baseline, close to the net or even from outside the field of play.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] If the ball is set for the attack by hitting the ball in the air and allowing for a bounce, this is called an indirect set.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The setter has to calculate the trajectory of the hit so that the bounce is at its highest point approximately 2.5 - 3.0 m in height, as this is the most effective height for an attacker to jump and strike the ball over the net.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The field conditions, distance to the net and possibly the wind direction all have to be taken into account when performing the set.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In addition, the ball should ideally have some forward spin so that the attacker can use this forward momentum in their attacking hit.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The setter can also hit the ball so that it is hit directly by the attacker without the ball first touching the ground; this is called a direct set.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The setter will often call "direct" or "indirect" prior to the set, to allow the attacker to adjust their approach.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Most sets are performed by the setter, however in many situations one of the attackers will be required to set due either to positioning, or the setter having already been forced to hit in defense.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] A good attacker must also be competent in setting the ball.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] A good attacker will be able to hit the ball with high impact (good hits will reach speeds of over 100 km/h), be able to access weaknesses in the positional play of the opponent and have a great repertoire of strokes.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The primary attacker is positioned next to the server, who acts as the secondary attacker.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The attacker uses the forward spin of a well-placed ball from a set to jump and hit it with full force into the gaps of opposing defenses.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Ideally, the attacker must be unpredictable to the opposition, ensuring the direction and speed of the attack can not be predicted by the defense until the hit takes place.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] As with the server, the attacker has a wide range of possible variations for attack, but the choice and effectiveness of each hit are particularly dependent on the success or failure of his team's ability to set up the attack from defense.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] For indoor fistball, the dimensions of the court change the approach of the attack, as the run-out section for indoor play is usually very limited due to the close proximity of walls.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] This fact is exploited by the setter, who will try to place the ball just about the net so that the attacker can hit the ball sharply across the court, restricting the opponents ability to get behind the ball before it hits the wall.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In order to stop this occurring, the opponent must attempt to block the ball at the net, similar to volleyball.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] This has significant effect on the formation and strategy of defending teams.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] A fistball game is controlled by a referee, who is assisted by two linesmen.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The referee has sole decision-making power.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] They make the final decision on all points or errors.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Since the linesmen are relatively far away from the referee, they are also responsible for observing the sidelines on his side of the field.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The linesmen are stationed in the opposite corners of the field from the referee, and use flags to signal their calls.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Their task is to make judgements on line calls, similar to a soccer linesman.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The observation area of the two linesmen is dependent on which of the two teams is currently attacking and which is defending.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The linesman on the attacking side is responsible for the entire sideline to the end, and therefore he or she turns to face the side line.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The linesman on the defending side is level with the base line and is therefore solely responsible for observing that line.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The linesmen change their observation areas as the play changes between attack and defense.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In addition to displaying off balls (flag held upwards) or good balls (flag held downwards) the referee is used to rule violations or other important game situations, such as substitutions, injuries, unsportsmanlike conduct etc.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The biggest international competition in fistball is the Fistball World Championships, currently held every four years.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] All member countries of the IFA are invited to participate in each event, with 10-12 teams usually qualifying for the tournament.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The competition location changes with each event, but is usually held in either Europe or South America.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The Fistball World Championship for women is held one year prior to the Fistball World Championship for men, and generally in a different host country to the one chosen for the subsequent men's tournament.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In the men's tournament, Germany, Austria, Switzerland, Brazil, Argentina, Chile, Namibia and Italy have competed in every tournament since 1990, while Serbia, USA and Japan have also been frequent participants.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The first Fistball World Championship was held for men in 1968, and for women in 1994.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] The top five teams from the Men's Fistball World Championships are also invited to compete in the fistball category of the World Games, also held every four years.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] If the host nation is a member of the IFA the sixth team is the fistball team of the host nation, otherwise the sixth placed team at the most recent World Championship is invited.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] While not directly facilitated by the IFA, this event has significant prestige.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] In addition to World Championships, international continental competitions are held for teams within Europe, South America and, most recently, Asia.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] For club competitions, the Fistball World Cup is held every year for both indoor and outdoor competitions, with the best clubs in the world competing.
[src:ballon-au-poing/fistball] Individual European and South American championships are also held for clubs, which are used as qualification for the World Cup competition.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Metropolitan France was settled during the Iron Age by Celtic tribes known as Gauls before Rome annexed the area in 51 BC, leading to a distinct Gallo-Roman culture.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In the Early Middle Ages, the Franks formed the kingdom of Francia, which became the heartland of the Carolingian Empire.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Treaty of Verdun of 843 partitioned the empire, with West Francia evolving into the Kingdom of France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In the High Middle Ages, France was a powerful but decentralised feudal kingdom, but from the mid-14th to the mid-15th centuries, France was plunged into a dynastic conflict with England known as the Hundred Years' War.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In the 16th century, French culture flourished during the French Renaissance, and a French colonial empire emerged.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Internally, France was dominated by the conflict with the House of Habsburg and the French Wars of Religion between Catholics and Huguenots.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France was successful in the Thirty Years' War and further increased its influence during the reign of Louis XIV.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The French Revolution of 1789 overthrew the Ancien Régime and produced the Declaration of the Rights of Man, which expresses the nation's ideals to this day.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France reached its political and military zenith in the early 19th century under Napoleon Bonaparte, subjugating much of continental Europe and establishing the First French Empire.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Its collapse initiated a period of relative decline during which France endured the Bourbon Restoration until the founding of the French Second Republic, which was succeeded by the Second French Empire upon Napoleon III's takeover.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] His empire collapsed during the Franco-Prussian War in 1870.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] This led to the establishment of the French Third Republic, and a period of economic prosperity and cultural and scientific flourishing known as the Belle Époque.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France was one of the major participants of World War I, from which it emerged victorious at great human and economic cost.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] It was among the Allies of World War II, but it surrendered and was occupied by Germany in 1940.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Following its liberation in 1944, the short-lived Fourth Republic was established and later dissolved over the course of the Algerian War.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The current Fifth Republic, a semi-presidential system, was formed in 1958 by Charles de Gaulle.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Algeria and most French colonies became independent in the 1960s, with the majority retaining close economic and military ties with France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France retains its centuries-long status as a global centre of art, science, cuisine and philosophy.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] It hosts the fourth-largest number of UNESCO World Heritage Sites, with 54 in total, and is the world's leading tourist destination, having received 102 million foreign visitors in 2025.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] A developed country, France has a high nominal per capita income globally, and its economy ranks among the largest in the world by both nominal GDP and PPP-adjusted GDP.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] It is a great power, being one of the five permanent members of the United Nations Security Council and an official nuclear-weapon state.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The country is part of multiple international organisations and forums.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Originally applied to the whole Frankish Empire, the name *France* comes from the Latin *Francia*, or 'realm of the Franks'.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] It has been suggested that the meaning 'free' was adopted because after the conquest of Gaul, only Franks were free of taxation, or more generally because they had the status of freemen in contrast to servants or slaves.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] It is traditionally derived from the Proto-Germanic word **frankōn*, which translates as 'javelin' or 'lance' (the throwing axe of the Franks was known as the *francisca*), although these weapons may have been named because of their use by the Franks, not the other way around.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In English, 'France' is pronounced /fræns/ *FRANSS* in American English and /frɑːns/ *FRAHNSS* or /fræns/ *FRANSS* in British English.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The pronunciation with /ɑː/ is mostly confined to accents with the trap–bath split such as Received Pronunciation, though it can be also heard in some other dialects such as Cardiff English.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The oldest traces of archaic humans in what is now France date from approximately 1.8 million years ago.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Neanderthals occupied the region into the Upper Paleolithic era but were slowly replaced by *Homo sapiens* around 35,000 BC.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] This period witnessed the emergence of cave painting in the Dordogne and Pyrenees, including at Lascaux, dated to c.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] At the end of the Last Glacial Period (10,000 BC), the climate became milder; from approximately 7,000 BC, this part of Western Europe entered the Neolithic era, and its inhabitants became sedentary.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] After demographic and agricultural development between the 4th and 3rd millennia BC, metallurgy appeared, initially working gold, copper and bronze, then later iron.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France has numerous megalithic sites from the Neolithic, including the Carnac stones site (approximately 3,300 BC).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In 600 BC, Ionian Greeks from Phocaea founded the colony of Massalia (present-day Marseille).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Celtic tribes penetrated parts of eastern and northern France, spreading through the rest of the country between the 5th and 3rd century BC.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Around 390 BC, the Gallic chieftain Brennus and his troops made their way to Roman Italy, defeated the Romans in the Battle of the Allia, and besieged and ransomed Rome.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] This left Rome weakened, and the Gauls continued to harass the region until 345 BC when they entered into a peace treaty.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] But the Romans and the Gauls remained adversaries for centuries.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Around 125 BC, the south of Gaul was conquered by the Romans, who called this region *Provincia Nostra* ("Our Province"), which evolved into Provence in French.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Julius Caesar conquered the remainder of Gaul and overcame a revolt by Gallic chieftain Vercingetorix in 52 BC.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Gaul was divided by Augustus into provinces, and many cities were founded during the Gallo-Roman period, including Lugdunum (present-day Lyon), the capital of the Gauls.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In 250–290 AD, Roman Gaul suffered a crisis with its fortified borders attacked by barbarians.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The situation improved in the first half of the 4th century, a period of revival and prosperity.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In 312, Emperor Constantine I converted to Christianity.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Christians, who had been persecuted, increased.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] However, the onset of the 5th century marked the resumption of major tribal migrations.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Teutonic tribes invaded the region, the Visigoths settling in the southwest, the Burgundians along the Rhine Valley, and the Franks in the north.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In late antiquity, Gaul was divided into Germanic kingdoms and a remaining Gallo-Roman territory.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Celtic Britons, fleeing the Anglo-Saxon settlement of Britain, settled in west Armorica; the Armorican peninsula was renamed Brittany, and Celtic culture was revived.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The first leader to unite all Franks was Clovis I, who began his reign as king of the Salian Franks in 481, routing the last forces of the Roman governors in 486.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Clovis said he would be baptised a Christian in the event of victory against the Visigothic Kingdom, which was said to have guaranteed the battle.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Clovis regained the southwest from the Visigoths and was baptised in 508.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Clovis was the first Germanic conqueror after the Fall of the Western Roman Empire to convert to Catholic Christianity; thus France was given the title "Eldest daughter of the Church" by the papacy, and French kings were called "the Most Christian Kings of France".
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Franks embraced the Christian Gallo-Roman culture, and Gaul was renamed *Francia* ("Land of the Franks").
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Germanic Franks adopted Romanic languages.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Clovis made Paris his capital and established the Merovingian dynasty, but his kingdom would not survive his death.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Franks treated land as a private possession and divided it among their heirs, so four kingdoms emerged from that of Clovis: Paris, Orléans, Soissons, and Rheims.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The last Merovingian kings lost power to their mayors of the palace (head of household).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] One mayor of the palace, Charles Martel, defeated an Umayyad invasion at the Battle of Tours in 732.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] His son, Pepin the Short, seized the crown of Francia from the weakened Merovingians and founded the Carolingian dynasty.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Pepin's son Charlemagne reunited the Frankish kingdoms and built an empire across Western and Central Europe.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Proclaimed Holy Roman Emperor by Pope Leo III and thus establishing the French government's longtime historical association with the Catholic Church, Charlemagne tried to revive the Western Roman Empire and its cultural grandeur.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Charlemagne's son Louis I kept the empire united, however in 843 it was divided between Louis' three sons into East Francia, Middle Francia and West Francia.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] West Francia approximated the area occupied by modern France and was its precursor.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Throughout the 9th and 10th centuries, incessant Viking raids severely weakened the Carolingian monarchy, accelerating the fragmentation of West Francia into a decentralised, feudal society.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] As central authority faltered, local nobility secured hereditary rights to their titles and lands, creating a system where the king's authority became more religious and symbolic than secular, frequently challenged by powerful territorial princes.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] After the Battle of Hastings in 1066, William the Conqueror added "King of England" to his titles, becoming vassal and the equal of the king of France, creating recurring tensions.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Carolingian dynasty ruled France until 987, when Hugh Capet was crowned king of the Franks.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] His descendants unified the country through wars and inheritance.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] From 1190, the Capetian rulers began to be referred as "kings of France" rather than "kings of the Franks".
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Later kings expanded their directly possessed *domaine royal* to cover over half of modern France by the 15th century.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Royal authority became more assertive, centred on a hierarchically conceived society distinguishing nobility, clergy, and commoners.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The nobility played a prominent role in Crusades to restore Christian access to the Holy Land.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] French knights made up most reinforcements in the 200 years of the Crusades, in such a fashion that the Arabs referred to crusaders as *Franj*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] French Crusaders imported French into the Levant, making Old French the base of the *lingua franca* ("Frankish language") of the Crusader states.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Albigensian Crusade was launched in 1209 to eliminate the heretical Cathars in the southwest of modern-day France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] From the 11th century, the House of Plantagenet, rulers of the County of Anjou, established its dominion over the surrounding provinces of Maine and Touraine, then built an "empire" from England to the Pyrenees, covering half of modern France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Tensions between France and the Plantagenet empire would last a hundred years, until Philip II of France conquered most of its continental possessions between 1202 and 1214 and defeated the Angevin coalition at the Battle of Bouvines, leaving only England and Aquitaine to the Plantagenets.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Following this victory, France became the most prosperous and powerful kingdom in Europe.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Charles IV the Fair died without an heir in 1328.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The crown passed to Philip of Valois rather than Edward Plantagenet, who had become Edward III of England the previous year.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] During the reign of Philip, the monarchy reached the height of its medieval power.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Edward contested Philip's throne in 1337, beginning the intermittent Hundred Years' War between England and France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Boundaries changed, but landholdings inside France by English kings remained extensive for decades.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] With charismatic leaders such as Joan of Arc, French counterattacks won back most English continental territories.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France was struck by the Black Death, from which half of the 17 million population died.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The French Renaissance saw cultural development and standardisation of French, which became the official language of France and Europe's aristocracy.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France became rivals of the House of Habsburg during the Italian Wars, which would dictate much of their later foreign policy until the mid-18th century.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] French explorers claimed lands in the Americas, paving expansion of the French colonial empire.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The rise of Protestantism led France to a civil war known as the French Wars of Religion.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] This forced Huguenots to flee to Protestant regions such as the British Isles and Switzerland.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The wars were ended by Henri IV's Edict of Nantes, which granted some freedom of religion to the Huguenots.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Spanish troops assisted the Catholics from 1589 to 1594 and invaded France in 1597.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Spain and France returned to all-out war between 1635 and 1659.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Franco-Spanish War cost France 300,000 casualties; total deaths on both sides were 200,000.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Under Louis XIII, Cardinal Richelieu promoted centralisation of the state and reinforced royal power.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] He destroyed castles of defiant lords and denounced the use of private armies.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] By the end of the 1620s, Richelieu established "the royal monopoly of force".
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France fought in the Thirty Years' War, supporting the Protestant side against the Habsburgs.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] From the 16th to the 19th century, France was responsible for about 10% of the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] During Louis XIV's minority, trouble known as The Fronde occurred.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] This rebellion was driven by feudal lords and sovereign courts as a reaction to the royal absolute power.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The monarchy reached its peak during the 17th century and reign of Louis XIV, during which France further increased its influence.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] By turning lords into courtiers at the Palace of Versailles, his command of the military went unchallenged.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] By the mid-17th century, France had emerged as the dominant power in Europe.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Under the reign of Louis XIV, it built Europe's strongest army, fought a series of wars, and experienced remarkable artistic and scientific flourishing.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] It also became the most populous European country and had tremendous influence over European politics, economy, and culture.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] French became the most-used language in diplomacy, science, and literature until the 20th century.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France took control of territories in the Americas, Africa and Asia.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In 1685, Louis XIV revoked the Edict of Nantes, forcing thousands of Huguenots into exile and published the *Code Noir* providing the legal framework for slavery and expelling Jews from French colonies.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Under the wars of Louis XV, France lost New France and most Indian possessions after its defeat in the Seven Years' War (1756–1763).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Its European territory kept growing, however, with acquisitions such as Lorraine and Corsica.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Louis XV's weak rule, including the decadence of his court, discredited the monarchy, which in part paved the way for the French Revolution.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Louis XVI supported America with money, fleets and armies, helping them win independence from Great Britain.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France gained revenge but verged on bankruptcy—a factor that contributed to the Revolution.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Some of the Enlightenment occurred in French intellectual circles, and scientific breakthroughs, such as the naming of oxygen and the first hot air balloon carrying passengers, were achieved by French scientists.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] French explorers took part in the voyages of scientific exploration through maritime expeditions.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Enlightenment philosophy, in which reason is advocated as the primary source of legitimacy, undermined the power of and support for the monarchy and was a factor in the Revolution.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The French Revolution was a period of political and societal change that began with the Estates General of 1789, and ended with the coup of 18 Brumaire in 1799 and the formation of the French Consulate.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Many of its ideas are fundamental principles of liberal democracy, while its values and institutions remain central to modern political discourse.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Its causes were a combination of social, political and economic factors, which the *Ancien Régime* proved unable to manage.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] A financial crisis and social distress led in May 1789 to the convocation of the Estates General, which was converted into a National Assembly in June.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Storming of the Bastille on 14 July led to a series of radical measures by the Assembly, among them the abolition of feudalism, state control over the Catholic Church in France, and a declaration of rights.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The next three years were dominated by a struggle for political control, exacerbated by economic depression.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Military defeats following the outbreak of the French Revolutionary Wars in April 1792 resulted in the insurrection of 10 August 1792.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The monarchy was abolished and replaced by the French First Republic in September, while Louis XVI was executed in January 1793.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] After another revolt in June 1793, the constitution was suspended and power passed from the National Convention to the Committee of Public Safety.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] About 16,000 people were executed in a Reign of Terror, which ended in July 1794.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Weakened by external threats and internal opposition, the Republic was replaced in 1795 by the Directory.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In 1799, the Consulate seized power in a coup led by Napoleon.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Napoleon became First Consul in 1799 and later Emperor of the French Empire.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Changing sets of European coalitions declared wars on Napoleon's empire.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] His armies conquered most of continental Europe with swift victories such as the Austerlitz and battles of Jena-Auerstadt.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Members of the Bonaparte family were appointed monarchs in some of the newly established kingdoms.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] These victories led to the worldwide expansion of French revolutionary ideals and reforms, such as the metric system, Napoleonic Code and Declaration of the Rights of Man.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In 1812 Napoleon attacked Russia, reaching Moscow.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Thereafter his army disintegrated through supply problems, disease, Russian attacks, and finally winter.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] After this catastrophic campaign and the ensuing uprising of European monarchies against his rule, Napoleon was defeated.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] About a million Frenchmen died during the Napoleonic Wars, including 306,000 killed.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] After his brief return from exile, Napoleon was finally defeated in 1815 at the Battle of Waterloo, and the Bourbon monarchy was restored with new constitutional limitations.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The discredited Bourbon dynasty was overthrown by the July Revolution of 1830, which established the constitutional July Monarchy; French troops began the conquest of Algeria.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Unrest led to the French Revolution of 1848 and the end of the July Monarchy.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The abolition of slavery and the introduction of male universal suffrage was re-enacted in 1848.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In 1852, president of the French Republic, Louis-Napoléon Bonaparte, Napoleon I's nephew, was proclaimed emperor of the Second Empire, as Napoleon III.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] He multiplied French interventions abroad, especially in Crimea, Mexico and Italy.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Napoleon III was unseated following defeat in the Franco-Prussian War of 1870, and his regime was replaced by the Third Republic.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] By 1875, the French conquest of Algeria was complete, with approximately 825,000 Algerians killed from famine, disease, and violence.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France suffered an estimated 10,000 killed and 35,000 wounded across all colonial campaigns.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] A few thousand died in Mexico or Vietnam, but the vast majority perished in Algeria.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Disease claimed an even heavier toll; one estimate puts total French and Foreign Legion deaths from battle and disease for the entire 19th century at 110,000.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France had colonial possessions since the beginning of the 17th century, but in the 19th and 20th centuries its empire extended significantly and became the second-largest behind the British Empire.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Including metropolitan France, the total area reached almost 13 million square kilometres in the 1920s and 1930s, 9% of the world's land.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Known as the *Belle Époque*, the turn of the century was characterised by optimism, regional peace, economic prosperity and technological, scientific and cultural innovations.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In 1905, state secularism was officially established.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] During World War I, France played a decisive role in defeating the Central Powers as part of the Triple Entente, while participating in the majority of the war's major battles fought on the Western Front.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] A rich industrial area in the north was occupied.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France and the Allies emerged victorious against the Central Powers at tremendous human cost.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] It left 1.4 million French soldiers dead, 4% of its population.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In addition, France suffered 4,266,000 wounded.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Interwar was marked by intense international tensions and social reforms introduced by the Popular Front government (e.g., annual leave, eight-hour workdays, women in government).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In 1940, France was invaded and quickly defeated by Nazi Germany.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France was divided into a German occupation zone in the north, an Italian occupation zone and an unoccupied territory, the rest of France, which consisted of southern France and the French empire.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Vichy government, an authoritarian regime collaborating with Germany, ruled the unoccupied territory.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Free France, the government-in-exile led by Charles de Gaulle, was set up in London.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] From 1942 to 1944, about 160,000 French citizens, including around 75,000 Jews, were deported to death and concentration camps.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] On 6 June 1944, the Allies invaded Normandy, and in August they invaded Provence.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Allies and French Resistance emerged victorious, and French sovereignty was restored with the Provisional Government of the French Republic (GPRF).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] This interim government, established by de Gaulle, continued to wage war against Germany and to purge collaborators from office.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] It made important reforms e.g. suffrage extended to women and the creation of a social security system.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] A new constitution resulted in the Fourth Republic (1946–1958), which saw strong economic growth (*les Trente Glorieuses*).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France was a founding member of NATO and attempted to regain control of French Indochina, but was defeated by the Viet Minh in 1954.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France faced another anti-colonialist conflict in Algeria, then part of France and home to over one million European settlers (Pied-Noir).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The French systematically used torture and repression, including extrajudicial killings to keep control.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] This conflict nearly led to a coup and civil war.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] During the May 1958 crisis, the weak Fourth Republic gave way to the Fifth Republic, which included a strengthened presidency.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The war concluded with the Évian Accords in 1962 which led to Algerian independence, at a high price: between half a million and one million deaths and over 2 million internally-displaced Algerians.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Around one million Pied-Noirs and Harkis fled from Algeria to France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] A vestige of the empire is the French overseas departments and territories.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] During the Cold War, de Gaulle pursued a policy of "national independence" towards the Western and Eastern blocs.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] He withdrew from NATO's military-integrated command (while remaining within the alliance), launched a nuclear development programme and made France the fourth nuclear power.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] He restored cordial Franco-German relations to create a European counterweight between American and Soviet spheres of influence.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] However, he opposed any development of a supranational Europe, favouring sovereign nations.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The revolt of May 1968 had an enormous social impact; it was a watershed moment when a conservative moral ideal (religion, patriotism, respect for authority) shifted to a more liberal moral ideal (secularism, individualism, sexual revolution).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Although the revolt was a political failure (the Gaullist party emerged stronger than before) it announced a split between the French and de Gaulle, who resigned.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In the post-Gaullist era, France remained one of the most developed economies in the world but faced crises that resulted in high unemployment rates and increasing public debt.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In the late 20th and early 21st centuries, France has been at the forefront of the development of a supranational European Union, notably by signing the Maastricht Treaty in 1992, establishing the eurozone in 1999 and signing the Treaty of Lisbon in 2007.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France has fully reintegrated into NATO and since participated in most NATO-sponsored wars.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Since the 19th century, France has received many immigrants, often male foreign workers from European Catholic countries who generally returned home when not employed.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] During the 1970s France faced an economic crisis and allowed new immigrants (mostly from the Maghreb, in northwest Africa) to permanently settle in France with their families and acquire citizenship.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] It resulted in hundreds of thousands of Muslims living in subsidised public housing and suffering from high unemployment rates.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The government had a policy of assimilation of immigrants, where they were expected to adhere to French values and norms.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] From the 2000s, France experienced continued immigration from Africa, the Middle East, and Asia.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In addition, Calais became a transit area for migrants.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Opération Chammal, France's military efforts to contain ISIS, killed over 1,000 ISIS troops between 2014 and 2015.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The vast majority of France's territory and population is situated in Western Europe and is called Metropolitan France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] It is bordered by the North Sea in the north, the English Channel in the northwest, the Atlantic Ocean in the west and the Mediterranean Sea in the southeast.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Its land borders consist of Belgium and Luxembourg in the northeast, Germany and Switzerland in the east, Italy and Monaco in the southeast, and Andorra and Spain in the south and southwest.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Except for the northeast, most of France's land borders are roughly delineated by natural boundaries and geographic features: to the south, the Pyrenees and the Alps; to the southeast, Jura Mountains; and to the east, the Rhine river.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Including Overseas France, it also borders Suriname and Brazil through French Guiana in South America, and the Netherlands through Saint Martin in the Caribbean.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Metropolitan France includes various coastal islands, of which the largest is Corsica.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Metropolitan France is situated mostly between latitudes 41° and 51° N, and longitudes 6° W and 10° E, on the western edge of Europe, and thus lies within the northern temperate zone.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Its continental part covers about 1000 km from north to south and from east to west.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Metropolitan France covers 551,500 square kilometres (212,935 sq mi), the largest among European Union members.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France's total land area, with its overseas departments and territories (excluding Adélie Land), is 643,801 km2 (248,573 sq mi), 0.45% of the total land area on Earth.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France possesses a wide variety of landscapes, from coastal plains in the north and west to the mountain ranges of the Alps in the southeast, the Massif Central in the south-central and Pyrenees in the southwest.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] With numerous overseas departments and territories scattered across the planet, France possesses the second-largest exclusive economic zone (EEZ) in the world, covering 11,035,000 km2 (4,261,000 sq mi).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Its EEZ covers approximately 8% of the total surface of all the EEZs of the world.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Metropolitan France has a wide variety of topographic sets and natural landscapes.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] During the Hercynian uplift in the Paleozoic Era, the Armorican Massif, the Massif Central, the Morvan, the Vosges and Ardennes ranges and the island of Corsica were formed.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] These massifs delineate several sedimentary basins such as the Aquitaine Basin in the southwest and the Paris Basin in the north.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Various routes of natural passage, such as the Rhône Valley, allow easy communication.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Alpine, Pyrenean and Jura Mountains are much younger and have less eroded forms.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] At 4,810.45 metres (15,782 ft) above sea level, Mont Blanc in the Alps is the highest point in Western Europe.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] 60% of municipalities are classified as having moderate seismic risk.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The coastlines offer contrasting landscapes: mountain ranges along the French Riviera, coastal cliffs such as the Côte d'Albâtre, and wide sandy plains in the Languedoc.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Corsica lies off the Mediterranean coast.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France has an extensive river system consisting of the four major rivers: the Seine, the Loire, the Garonne, the Rhône and their tributaries, whose combined catchment includes over 62% of the metropolitan territory.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Rhône divides the Massif Central from the Alps and flows into the Mediterranean Sea at the Camargue.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Garonne meets the Dordogne just after Bordeaux, forming the Gironde estuary, the largest estuary in Western Europe which after approximately 100 kilometres (62 mi) empties into the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Other water courses drain towards the Meuse and Rhine along the northeastern borders.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France has 11,000,000 km2 (4,200,000 sq mi) of marine waters within three oceans under its jurisdiction, of which 97% are overseas.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] On June 28, 2019, in Vérargues, the temperature reached 46 °C, setting a temperature record in Metropolitan France since records began.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Climate change means that this kind of heatwave in France can be expected to occur 10 times more frequently than it would have done a century ago.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France was one of the first countries to create an environment ministry, in 1971.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France is ranked 19th by carbon dioxide emissions due to the country's heavy investment in nuclear power following the 1973 oil crisis, which now accounts for 75 per cent of its electricity production and results in less pollution.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] According to the 2020 Environmental Performance Index conducted by Yale and Columbia, France was the fifth most environmentally conscious country in the world.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Like all European Union state members, France agreed to cut carbon emissions by at least 20% of 1990 levels by 2020.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] As of 2009, carbon dioxide emissions per capita are lower than that of China.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The country was set to impose a carbon tax in 2009; however, the plan was abandoned due to fears of it burdening French businesses.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Forests account for 31 per cent of the land area—the fourth-highest proportion in Europe—representing an increase of 7 per cent since 1990.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The forests are some of the most diverse in Europe, comprising more than 140 species of trees.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 4.52/10, ranking it 123rd globally.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] There are nine national parks and 46 natural parks.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France is a representative democracy organised as a unitary semi-presidential republic.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Democratic traditions and values are deeply rooted in French culture, identity and politics.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Constitution of the Fifth Republic was approved by referendum in 1958, establishing a framework consisting of executive, legislative and judicial branches.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] It sought to address the instability of the Third and Fourth Republics by combining elements of both the parliamentary and presidential systems, while greatly strengthening the authority of the executive relative to the legislature.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The president, who is Emmanuel Macron since 2017, is the head of state, elected directly by universal adult suffrage for a five-year term.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The prime minister, who is Sébastien Lecornu since 2025, is the head of government, appointed by the president to lead the government.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The president has the power to dissolve parliament or circumvent it by submitting referendums directly to the people; the president also appoints judges and civil servants, negotiates and ratifies international agreements, and serves as commander-in-chief of the French Armed Forces.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The prime minister determines public policy and oversees the civil service, with an emphasis on domestic matters.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In the 2022 presidential election, Macron was re-elected.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Two months later in the legislative elections, Macron lost his parliamentary majority and had to form a minority government.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The legislature consists of the French Parliament, a bicameral body made up of a lower house, the National Assembly, and an upper house, the Senate.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Legislators in the National Assembly, known as *députés*, represent local constituencies and are directly elected for five-year terms.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Assembly has the power to dismiss the government by majority vote.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Senators are chosen by an electoral college for six-year terms, with half the seats submitted to election every three years.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Senate's legislative powers are limited; in the event of disagreement between the two chambers, the National Assembly has the final say.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The parliament is responsible for determining the rules and principles concerning most areas of law, political amnesty, and fiscal policy; however, the government may draft specific details concerning most laws.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In the 2017 presidential and legislative elections, the radical centrist party La République En Marche!
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] (LREM) became the dominant force, overtaking both Socialists and Republicans.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] LREM's opponent in the second round of the 2017 and 2022 presidential elections was the growing far-right party National Rally (RN).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Since 2020, The Ecologists have performed well in mayoral elections in major cities while on a national level, the New Ecological and Social People's Union was the second-largest voting block elected to the lower house in 2022.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Right-wing populist RN became the largest opposition party in the National Assembly in 2022.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The electorate is constitutionally empowered to vote on amendments passed by the Parliament and bills submitted by the president.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Referendums have played a key role in shaping French politics and even foreign policy; voters have decided on such matters as Algeria's independence, the election of the president by popular vote, the formation of the EU, and the reduction of presidential term limits.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Since 2016, France is divided into 18 administrative regions: 13 regions in metropolitan France (including Corsica), and five overseas.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The regions are further subdivided into 101 departments, which are numbered mainly alphabetically.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The department number is used in postal codes and was formerly used on vehicle registration plates.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Among the 101 French departments, five (French Guiana, Guadeloupe, Martinique, Mayotte, and Réunion) are in overseas regions that are simultaneously overseas departments, enjoying the same status as metropolitan departments and are thereby included in the European Union.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The 101 departments are subdivided into 335 arrondissements, which are, in turn, subdivided into 2,054 cantons.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] These cantons are divided into 36,658 communes, which are municipalities with an elected municipal council.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Three communes—Paris, Lyon and Marseille—are subdivided into 45 municipal arrondissements.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Overseas collectivities and territories form part of the French Republic but do not form part of the European Union or its fiscal area (except for Saint Barthélemy, which seceded from Guadeloupe in 2007).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Pacific Collectivities of French Polynesia, Wallis and Futuna, and New Caledonia continue to use the CFP franc whose value is strictly linked to the euro.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France is a founding member of the United Nations and serves as one of the permanent members of the UN Security Council with veto rights.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In 2015 it was described as "the best networked state in the world" due to its membership in more international institutions than any other country; these include the G7, World Trade Organization, the Pacific Community and the Indian Ocean Commission.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] It is an associate member of the Association of Caribbean States and a leading member of the Organisation internationale de la Francophonie of 84 French-speaking countries.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] As a significant hub for international relations, France has the third-largest assembly of diplomatic missions, behind China and the United States.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] It also hosts the headquarters of several international organisations, including the OECD, UNESCO, Interpol, the International Bureau of Weights and Measures, and the OIF.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] French foreign policy after World War II has been largely shaped by membership in the European Union, of which it was a founding member.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Since the 1963 Élysée Treaty, France has developed close ties with reunified Germany to become the most influential driving force of the EU.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Since 1904 France has maintained an "Entente Cordiale" with the United Kingdom, and there has been a strengthening of ties between the countries, especially militarily.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France is a member of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), but under President Charles de Gaulle excluded itself from the joint military command in protest of the Special Relationship between the U.S. and UK, and to preserve the independence of French foreign and security policies.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Under Nicolas Sarkozy, France rejoined the NATO joint military command.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France retains strong political and economic influence in its former African colonies (*Françafrique*) and has supplied economic aid and troops for peacekeeping missions in Ivory Coast and Chad.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] From 2012 to 2021, France and other African states intervened in support of the Malian government in the Mali War.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In 2017, France was the world's fourth-largest donor of development aid in absolute terms.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The French Armed Forces (*Forces armées françaises*) are the military and paramilitary forces of France, under the president as commander-in-chief.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Together they are among the largest armed forces in the world and the largest in the EU.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] According to a 2015 study by Crédit Suisse, the French Armed Forces ranked as the world's sixth-most powerful military and the second most powerful in Europe.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France's annual military expenditure in 2023 was US$61.3 billion, or 2.1% of its GDP, making it the eighth biggest military spender in the world.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] There has been no national conscription since 1997.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France has been a recognised nuclear state since 1960.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] It is a party to both the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty and the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The French nuclear force (formerly known as "*Force de Frappe*") consists of four *Triomphant*-class submarines equipped with submarine-launched ballistic missiles.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France has major military industries and one of the largest aerospace sectors in the world.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The country has produced such equipment as the Dassault Rafale fighter, the *Charles de Gaulle* aircraft carrier, the Exocet missile, and the Leclerc tank, among others.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France is a major arms seller, with most of its arsenal's designs available for the export market, except for nuclear-powered devices.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Weapons exported totalled 27 billion euros in 2022, up from 11.7 billion euros the previous year.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The UAE contributed more than 16 billion euros arms to the French total.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Among the largest French defence companies are Dassault, Thales and Safran.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Directorate General for External Security is a component of the Armed Forces under the authority of the Ministry of Defence.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The General Directorate for Internal Security operates under the authority of the Ministry of the Interior.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France's cybersecurity capabilities are regularly ranked as some of the most robust of any nation in the world.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France uses a civil legal system, wherein law arises primarily from written statutes; judges are not to make law, but merely to interpret it (though the amount of judicial interpretation in certain areas makes it equivalent to case law in a common law system).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Basic principles of the rule of law were laid in the Napoleonic Code (which was largely based on royal law codified under King Louis XIV).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In agreement with the principles of the Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen, the law should only prohibit actions detrimental to society.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] French law is divided into two principal areas: private law and public law.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Private law includes, in particular, civil law and criminal law.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Public law includes, in particular, administrative law and constitutional law.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] However, in practical terms, French law comprises three principal areas of law: civil law, criminal law, and administrative law.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Criminal laws can only address the future and not the past (criminal *ex post facto* laws are prohibited).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] To be applicable, every law must be officially published in the *Journal officiel de la République française*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France does not recognise religious law as a motivation for the enactment of prohibitions; it has long abolished blasphemy laws and sodomy laws.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] However, "offences against public decency" or disturbing public order have been used to repress public expressions of homosexuality or street prostitution.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France generally has a positive reputation regarding LGBTQ rights.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Since 1999, civil unions for homosexual couples have been permitted, and since 2013, same-sex marriage and LGBT adoption are legal.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] France has laws against racism and antisemitism, while the 1990 Gayssot Act prohibits Holocaust denial.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In 2024, France became the first nation in the European Union to explicitly protect abortion in its constitution.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Freedom of religion is constitutionally guaranteed by the 1789 Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The 1905 French law on the Separation of the Churches and the State is the basis for *laïcité* (state secularism): the state does not formally recognise any religion, except in Alsace-Moselle, which continues to subsidise education and clergy of Catholicism, Lutheranism, Calvinism, and Judaism.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] Nonetheless, France does recognise religious associations.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] The Parliament has listed many religious movements as dangerous cults since 1995 and has banned wearing conspicuous religious symbols in schools since 2004.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] In 2010, it banned the wearing of face-covering Islamic veils in public; human rights groups such as Amnesty International and Human Rights Watch described the law as discriminatory towards Muslims.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p01] However, it is supported by most of the population.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France has a social market economy characterised by sizeable government involvement and diversified sectors.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] For two centuries, it has consistently ranked among the ten largest globally; as of 2025 it is the world's ninth largest by purchasing power parity and second largest in the EU, after Germany.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Considered a great power with considerable economic strength, it is a member of the Group of Seven leading industrialised countries, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), and the G20.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France ranked 13th in the 2025 Global Innovation Index.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The economy is highly diversified; services represent two-thirds of both the workforce and GDP, while the industrial sector accounts for a fifth of GDP and a similar proportion of employment.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France is the third-biggest manufacturing country in Europe, behind Germany and Italy, and ranks eighth in the world by manufacturing output, at 1.9 per cent.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Less than 2 per cent of GDP is generated by the primary sector, namely agriculture; the agricultural sector is among the largest in value and leads the EU in overall production.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 2018 France was the fifth-largest trading nation and second-largest in Europe, with the value of exports representing over a fifth of GDP.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Its membership in the eurozone and the broader European single market facilitates access to capital, goods, services, and skilled labour.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Despite protectionist policies over certain industries, particularly in agriculture, France has generally played a leading role in fostering free trade and commercial integration in Europe to enhance its economy.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 2019, it ranked first in Europe and 13th in the world in foreign direct investment, with European countries and the United States being leading sources.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] According to the Bank of France (founded in 1800), the leading recipients of foreign direct investment are manufacturing, real estate, finance and insurance.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The Paris Region has the highest concentration of multinational firms in mainland Europe.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Under the doctrine of *dirigisme*, the government historically played a major role in the economy; policies such as indicative planning and nationalisation are credited for contributing to three decades of unprecedented postwar economic growth known as *Trente Glorieuses*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] At its peak in 1982, the public sector accounted for one-fifth of industrial employment and over four-fifths of the credit market.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Beginning in the late 20th century, regulations and state involvement in the economy were loosened, with most leading companies becoming privately owned; state ownership still dominates transportation, defence and broadcasting.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Policies aimed at promoting economic dynamism and privatisation have improved France's economic standing globally: it is among the world's 10 most innovative countries in the 2020 Bloomberg Innovation Index, and the 15th most competitive according to the 2019 Global Competitiveness Report.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The Paris stock exchange is one of the oldest in the world, created in 1724.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Some examples of the most valuable French companies include LVMH, L'Oréal and Sociéte Générale.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France has historically been one of the world's major agricultural centres and remains a "global agricultural powerhouse"; France is the world's sixth-biggest exporter of agricultural products, generating a trade surplus of over €7.4 billion.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Nicknamed "the granary of the old continent", over half its total land area is farmland, of which 45 per cent is devoted to permanent field crops such as cereals.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The country's diverse climate, extensive arable land, modern farming technology, and EU subsidies have made it Europe's leading agricultural producer and exporter.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] With 102 million international tourist arrivals in 2025, France is the world's top tourist destination and ranks third in tourism-derived income due to shorter visit durations.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Disneyland Paris is Europe's most popular theme park, with 15 million combined visitors to the resort's Disneyland Park and Walt Disney Studios Park in 2009.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] With more than 10 million tourists per year, the French Riviera is the second leading tourist destination in the country, after the Paris Region.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] With 6 million tourists per year, the castles of the Loire Valley (French: *châteaux*) and the Loire Valley are the third leading tourist destination.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France has 54 sites inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage List, ranking it fourth worldwide by number of sites.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France features cities of high cultural interest, beaches and seaside resorts, ski resorts, as well as rural regions that many enjoy for their beauty and tranquillity (green tourism).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Small and picturesque villages are promoted through the association *Les Plus Beaux Villages de France* (literally "The Most Beautiful Villages of France").
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The "Remarkable Gardens" label is a list of the over 200 gardens classified by the Ministry of Culture.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] This label is intended to protect and promote remarkable gardens and parks.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France attracts many religious pilgrims on their way to St.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] James or to Lourdes, a town in the Hautes-Pyrénées that hosts several million visitors a year.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France is the world's tenth-largest producer of electricity. Électricité de France (EDF), which is majority-owned by the French government, is the country's main producer and distributor of electricity and one of the world's largest electric utility companies, ranking third in revenue globally.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 2018, EDF produced roughly one-fifth of the EU's electricity, primarily from nuclear power.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 2021, France was the biggest energy exporter in Europe, mostly to the UK and Italy, and the largest net exporter of electricity in the world.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Since the 1973 oil crisis, France has pursued a strong policy of energy security, namely through heavy investment in nuclear energy.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] It is one of 32 countries with nuclear power plants, ranking second in the world by the number of operational nuclear reactors at 56.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Consequently, 70% of its electricity is generated by nuclear power, the highest proportion in the world by a wide margin; only Slovakia and Ukraine also derive a majority of electricity from nuclear power, at roughly 53% and 51%, respectively.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France is considered a world leader in nuclear technology, with reactors and fuel products being major exports.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The significant reliance on nuclear power has resulted in comparatively slower adoption of renewable energy relative to other Western nations.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Nevertheless, between 2008 and 2019, its production capacity from renewable energies rose consistently and nearly doubled.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Hydropower is by far the leading source, accounting for over half of renewable energy sources and contributing 13% of its electricity the third highest proportion in Europe.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Most hydroelectric plants, such as Eguzon, Étang de Soulcem, and Lac de Vouglans, are managed by EDF.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France aims to further expand hydropower into 2040.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The railway network in France stretches 29,473 kilometres (18,314 mi) as of 2008 and is the second most extensive in Western Europe after Germany's.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] It is operated by the SNCF, and high-speed trains include Thalys, Eurostar and TGV, which travels at 320 km/h (199 mph).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Eurostar and LeShuttle connect with the United Kingdom through the Channel Tunnel.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Rail connections exist to all other neighbouring countries in Europe except Andorra.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Intra-urban connections are also well developed, with most major cities having underground or tramway services complementing bus services.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] There are approximately 1,027,183 kilometres (638,262 mi) of serviceable roadway, ranking it the most extensive network of the European continent.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The Paris Region is enveloped with a dense network of roads and highways, which connect it with virtually all parts of the country.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Roads also handle substantial international traffic, connecting with cities in neighbouring countries.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] There is no annual registration fee or road tax; usage of the mostly privately owned motorways is through tolls except in the vicinity of large communes.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The new car market is dominated by domestic brands such as Renault, Peugeot and Citroën.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France possesses the Millau Viaduct, the world's tallest bridge, and has built many important bridges such as the Pont de Normandie.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Diesel and petrol-driven cars and lorries cause a large part of the country's air pollution and greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Charles de Gaulle Airport, located in the vicinity of Paris, is the largest and busiest airport in the country, handling the vast majority of popular and commercial traffic and connecting Paris with virtually all major cities across the world.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Air France is the national carrier airline, although numerous private airline companies provide domestic and international travel services.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] There are ten major ports, the largest of which is in Marseille, which also is the largest bordering the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] 12,261 kilometres (7,619 mi) of waterways traverse France including the Canal du Midi, which connects the Mediterranean Sea to the Atlantic Ocean through the Garonne river.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] With an estimated population of 69,081,996 people, France is the 20th most populous country in the world, the third-most populous in Europe, and the second most populous in the European Union.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] For much of the 21st century, France has been an outlier among developed countries, particularly in Europe, for its relatively high rate of natural population growth; by birth rates alone, it was responsible for almost all natural population growth in the EU in 2006.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Between 2006 and 2016, France saw the second-highest overall increase in population in the EU and was one of four EU countries where natural births accounted for the most population growth.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] This was the highest rate since the end of the baby boom in 1973 and coincides with the rise in the total fertility rate from a nadir of 1.7 in 1994 to 2.0 in 2010.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Since 2011, the fertility rate has been steadily declining; it stood at 1.79 per woman in 2023, below the replacement rate of 2.1 and well below the high of 4.41 in 1800.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Fertility rate and crude birth rate nonetheless remain the highest in the EU and among the highest in Europe overall, where the average is 1.5.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The mean age of French women at the birth of their first child was 29.1, slightly younger than the EU average of 29.7.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Like many developed nations, the population is aging: The average age is 41.7 years, while roughly one-fifth of French people are 65 or over.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] It is projected that one in three French will be over 60 by 2024.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Life expectancy at birth is 82.7 years, the 12th highest in the world; French Polynesia and Réunion ranked fourth and 11th in life expectancy, at 84.07 years and 83.55, respectively.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] From 2006 to 2011, population growth averaged 0.6 percent per year; since 2011, annual growth has been between 0.4 and 0.5 percent annually, and France is projected to continue growing until 2044.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Immigrants are major contributors to this trend; in 2010, roughly one in four newborns (27 percent) in Metropolitan France had at least one foreign-born parent, and another 24 percent had at least one parent born outside Europe (excluding French overseas territories).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 2021, the share of children of foreign-born mothers was 23 percent.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The fertility rate in France dropped to 1.56 in 2025.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] This was the lowest rate since the end of the first world war.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] (Note: since its 2020 revision of metropolitan area borders, INSEE considers that Nice is a metropolitan area separate from the Cannes-Antibes metropolitan area; these two combined would have a population of 1,045,839, as of the 2023 census).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Rural flight was a perennial political issue throughout most of the 20th century.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Historically, French people were mainly of Celtic-Gallic origin, with a significant admixture of Italic (Romans) and Germanic (Franks) groups reflecting centuries of respective migration and settlement.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Through the course of the Middle Ages, France incorporated various neighbouring ethnic and linguistic groups, as evidenced by Breton elements in the west, Aquitanian in the southwest, Scandinavian in the northwest, Alemannic in the northeast, and Ligurian in the southeast.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 2004 the *Institut Montaigne* estimated that within Metropolitan France, 51 million people were white (85% of the population), 6 million were northwest African (10%), 2 million were black (3.3%), and 1 million were Asian (1.7%).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] There are also sizeable minorities of other European ethnic groups, namely Spanish, Portuguese, Polish, and Greek.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France has a significant Gitan (Romani) population, numbering between 20,000 and 400,000; many foreign Roma are expelled back to Bulgaria and Romania frequently.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] It is estimated that 40% of the French population is descended at least partially from the different waves of immigration since the early 20th century; between 1921 and 1935 alone, about 1.1 million net immigrants came to France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The next largest wave came in the 1960s when around 1.6 million *pieds-noirs* returned to France following the independence of its northwest African possessions of Algeria and Morocco.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] They were joined by numerous former colonial subjects from North and West Africa, as well as numerous European immigrants from Spain and Portugal.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France remains a major destination for immigrants, accepting about 200,000 legal immigrants annually.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 2005, it was Western Europe's leading recipient of asylum seekers, with an estimated 50,000 applications (albeit a 15% decrease from 2004).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 2010, France received about 48,100 asylum applications—placing it among the top five asylum recipients in the world.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In subsequent years it saw the number of applications increase, ultimately doubling to 100,412 in 2017.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The European Union allows free movement between the member states, although France established controls to curb Eastern European migration.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Foreigners' rights are established in the Code of Entry and Residence of Foreigners and of the Right to Asylum.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Immigration remains a contentious political issue.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 2008 INSEE estimated that the number of foreign-born immigrants was around 5 million (8% of the population), while their French-born descendants numbered 6.5 million, or 11% of the population.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Thus, nearly a fifth of the country's population were either first or second-generation immigrants, of which more than 5 million were of European origin and 4 million of Maghrebi ancestry.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 2008, France granted citizenship to 137,000 persons, mostly from Morocco, Algeria and Turkey.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 2022, more than 320,000 migrants came to France, with the majority coming from Africa.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 2014, the INSEE reported a significant increase in the number of immigrants coming from Spain, Portugal and Italy between 2009 and 2012.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] According to the institute, this increase resulted from the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Statistics on Spanish immigrants in France show a growth of 107 per cent between 2009 and 2012, with the population growing from 5,300 to 11,000.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Of the total of 229,000 foreigners coming to France in 2012, nearly 8% were Portuguese, 5% British, 5% Spanish, 4% Italian, 4% German, 3% Romanian, and 3% Belgian.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The official language is French, a Romance language derived from Latin.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Since 1635, the Académie Française has been the official authority on the French language, although its recommendations carry no legal weight.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] There are also regional languages spoken in France, such as Occitan, Breton, Catalan, Flemish (Dutch dialect), Alsatian (German dialect), Basque, and Corsican (Italian dialect).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Italian was the official language of Corsica up to 1859.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Although regional languages do not have the status of official languages, they are recognised by Article 75-1 of the constitution as part of France's heritage.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The government does not regulate the choice of language in publications by individuals, but the use of French is required by law in commercial and workplace communications.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The French government tries to promote French in the EU and globally through institutions such as the Organisation internationale de la Francophonie.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] There are 77 vernacular minority languages, eight spoken in Metropolitan France and 69 in the overseas territories.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France is a secular country in which freedom of religion is a constitutional right.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Alsace and Moselle, which were part of the German Empire when state secularism was established in France, is an exception since the local law stipulates official status and state funding for Lutheranism, Catholicism, and Judaism.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Catholicism has been the main religion in France for more than a millennium, and it was once the state religion.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Its role nowadays has been greatly reduced; nevertheless in 2012, among the 47,000 religious buildings in France, 94% were Catholic churches.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The government is prohibited from recognising specific rights to any religious community (with the exception of legacy statutes like those of military chaplains and the aforementioned local law in Alsace-Moselle).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] It recognises religious organisations according to formal legal criteria that do not address religious doctrine, and religious organisations are expected to refrain from intervening in policymaking.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Some religious groups, such as scientology, the Children of God, the Unification Church, and the Order of the Solar Temple, are considered cults (*sectes* in French) and are not granted the same status as recognised religions.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The French health care system is one of universal health care largely financed by government national health insurance.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In its 2000 assessment of world health care systems, the World Health Organization (WHO) found that France provided the "close to best overall health care" in the world.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The French health care system was ranked first worldwide by the WHO in 1997.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 2011, France spent 11.6% of its GDP on health care, or US$4,086 per capita, a figure much higher than the average spent by countries in Europe.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Approximately 77% of health expenditures are covered by government-funded agencies.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Care is generally free for people affected by chronic diseases such as cancer, AIDS or cystic fibrosis.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The life expectancy at birth is 80 years for men and 85.6 years for women.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] There are 3.2 physicians for every 1000 inhabitants, 5.7 hospital beds for every 1000 inhabitants, and average health care spending per capita was US$8,630 in 2022, representing 12.1% of GDP.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] As of 2007, approximately 140,000 inhabitants (0.4%) are living with HIV/AIDS.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 1802, Napoleon created the lycée, the second and final stage of secondary education that prepares students for higher education studies or a profession.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Jules Ferry is considered the father of the French modern school, leading reforms in the late 19th century that established free, secular and compulsory education (currently mandatory to age 16).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] French education is centralised and divided into three stages: primary, secondary, and higher education.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The Programme for International Student Assessment, coordinated by the OECD, ranked France's education as near the OECD average in 2018.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] School children in France reported greater concern about the disciplinary climate and behaviour in classrooms compared to other OECD countries.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The *Grandes écoles* have been criticised for alleged elitism, producing many if not most of France's high-ranking civil servants, CEOs and politicians.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France also supports a network of schools internationally through the Agency for French Education Abroad.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The network includes a mix of directly managed schools, subsidized institutions, and partner schools, and provides French education to students around the world.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The origins of a distinctly French art date back to the Middle Ages.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In the 12th century, Paris and its region saw the birth of Gothic art, known at the time as *Opus Francigenum* (lit.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] 'French work'), which from the cathedrals of Chartres, Amiens and Reims soon radiated throughout Europe, thanks to French architects and sculptors who went abroad.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] French art was very much influenced first by Flemish art then by Italian art at the time of the Renaissance.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Jean Fouquet, the most famous medieval French painter, is said to have been the first to travel to Italy and experience the Early Renaissance firsthand.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The Renaissance painting School of Fontainebleau was directly inspired by Italian painters such as Primaticcio and Rosso Fiorentino, who both worked in France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Two of the most famous French artists of the time of the Baroque era, Nicolas Poussin and Claude Lorrain, lived in Italy.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] French artists developed the rococo style in the early 18th century, as a more intimate evolution of the Baroque style, the works of the court-endorsed artists Antoine Watteau, François Boucher and Jean-Honoré Fragonard being the most representative in the country.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The French Revolution brought great changes, as Napoleon favoured artists of neoclassic style such as Jacques-Louis David and the highly influential Académie des Beaux-Arts defined the style known as Academism.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In the second part of the 19th century, France's influence over painting grew, with the development of new styles of painting such as Impressionism and Symbolism.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The most famous impressionist painters of the period were Camille Pissarro, Édouard Manet, Edgar Degas, Claude Monet and Auguste Renoir.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The second generation of impressionist-style painters, Paul Cézanne, Paul Gauguin, Toulouse-Lautrec and Georges Seurat, were also at the avant-garde of artistic evolutions, as well as the fauvist artists Henri Matisse, André Derain and Maurice de Vlaminck.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Cubism was developed by Georges Braque and the Spanish painter Pablo Picasso, who was living in Paris.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Other foreign artists also settled and worked in or near Paris, such as Vincent van Gogh and Wassily Kandinsky.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In the early 20th century and in particular during the interwar period, a loose collection of foreign artists of whom many were Jewish formed the School of Paris.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Amongst these artists were Marc Chagall, Amedeo Modigliani, Yitzhak Frenel, Jules Pascin and others.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The Second World War led to the deaths or exile of multiple artists, resulting in the relative fall of Paris' domination and centrality in the world art scene in favour of New York City.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] During the Middle Ages, many fortified castles were built by feudal nobles to mark their powers.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Some French castles that survive are Chinon, Château d'Angers, Château de Vincennes and the Cathar castles.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] During this era, France had been using Romanesque architecture like most of Western Europe.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Gothic architecture, originally named *Opus Francigenum* meaning "French work", was born in Île-de-France and was the first French style of architecture to be imitated throughout Europe.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Northern France is the home of some of the most important Gothic cathedrals and basilicas, the first of these being the Saint Denis Basilica (used as the royal necropolis); other important French Gothic cathedrals are Notre-Dame de Chartres and Notre-Dame d'Amiens.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The kings were crowned in another important Gothic church: Notre-Dame de Reims.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The final victory in the Hundred Years' War marked an important stage in the evolution of French architecture.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] It was the time of the French Renaissance and several artists from Italy were invited to the French court; many residential palaces were built in the Loire Valley, from 1450 as a first reference the Château de Montsoreau.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Examples of such residential castles include the Château de Chambord, the Château de Chenonceau, or the Château d'Amboise.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Following the Renaissance and the end of the Middle Ages, Baroque architecture replaced the traditional Gothic style.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Baroque architecture found greater success in the secular domain than in the religious one.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In the secular domain, the Palace of Versailles has many Baroque features.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Jules Hardouin-Mansart, who designed the extensions to Versailles, was one of the most influential French architects of the Baroque era; he is famous for his dome at Les Invalides.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Some of the most impressive provincial Baroque architecture is found in places that were not yet French such as Place Stanislas in Nancy.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] On the military architectural side, Vauban designed some of the most efficient fortresses in Europe and became an influential military architect; as a result, imitations of his works can be found all over Europe, the Americas, Russia and Turkey.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] After the Revolution, the Republicans favoured Neoclassicism although it was introduced in France before the revolution with such buildings as the Parisian Pantheon or the Capitole de Toulouse.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Built during the French First Empire, the Arc de Triomphe and Sainte Marie-Madeleine represent the best example of Empire style architecture.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Under Napoleon III, a wave of urbanism and architecture was given birth; extravagant buildings such as the neo-Baroque Palais Garnier were built.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The urban planning of the time was very organised and rigorous; most notably, Haussmann's renovation of Paris.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The architecture associated with this era is named Second Empire in English, the term being taken from the Second French Empire.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] At this time there was a strong Gothic resurgence across Europe and in France; the associated architect was Eugène Viollet-le-Duc.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In the late 19th century, Gustave Eiffel designed many bridges, such as the Garabit viaduct, and remains one of the most influential bridge designers of his time, although he is best remembered for the Eiffel Tower.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In the 20th century, French-Swiss architect Le Corbusier designed several buildings in France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] More recently, French architects have combined both modern and old architectural styles.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The Louvre Pyramid is an example of modern architecture added to an older building.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The most difficult buildings to integrate within French cities are skyscrapers, as they are visible from afar.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] For instance, in Paris since 1977, new buildings had to be under 37 metres (121 ft).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] A significant number of skyscrapers are located in the La Défense financial district.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Other massive buildings that are a challenge to integrate into their environment are large bridges; an example of the way this has been done is the Millau Viaduct.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Some famous modern French architects include Jean Nouvel, Dominique Perrault, Christian de Portzamparc and Paul Andreu.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The earliest French literature dates from the Middle Ages, when there were several languages and dialects, and writers used their own spelling and grammar.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Some authors of medieval texts, such as *Tristan and Iseult* and *Lancelot-Grail,* are unknown.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Three famous medieval authors are Chrétien de Troyes, Christine de Pizan (langue d'oïl), and Duke William IX of Aquitaine (langue d'oc).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Much medieval French poetry and literature was inspired by the legends of the Carolingian cycle, such as the *Song of Roland* and the chansons de geste.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The *Roman de Renart*, written in 1175 by Perrout de Saint Cloude, tells the story of the medieval character Reynard ('the Fox') and is another example of early French writing.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] An important 16th-century writer was François Rabelais, who wrote five popular early picaresque novels.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Rabelais was also in regular communication with Marguerite de Navarre, author of the *Heptaméron*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Michel de Montaigne's most famous work, *Essais*, started a literary genre.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] French literature and poetry flourished during the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Denis Diderot is best known as the main editor of the *Encyclopédie*, whose aim was to sum up all the knowledge of his century and to fight ignorance and obscurantism.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Charles Perrault was a prolific writer of children's fairy tales including *Puss in Boots*, *Cinderella*, *Sleeping Beauty* and *Bluebeard*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] At the start of the 19th century, symbolist poetry was an important movement, with poets such as Charles Baudelaire, Paul Verlaine and Stéphane Mallarmé.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Victor Hugo is sometimes seen as "the greatest French writer of all time" for excelling in all literary genres.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Hugo's verse has been compared to that of Shakespeare, Dante and Homer.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] His novel *Les Misérables* is widely seen as one of the greatest novels ever written, and *The Hunchback of Notre Dame* has remained immensely popular.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In the early 20th century France was a haven for literary freedom.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Works banned for obscenity in the US, the UK and other Anglophone nations were published in France decades before they were available in the respective authors' home countries.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The French were disinclined to punish literary figures for their writing, and prosecutions were rare.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Important writers of the 20th century include Marcel Proust, Louis-Ferdinand Céline, Jean Cocteau, Albert Camus, and Jean-Paul Sartre.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Antoine de Saint-Exupéry wrote *The Little Prince*, which is one of the best selling books in history.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Medieval French philosophy was dominated by Scholasticism until the emergence of Humanism in the Renaissance.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Modern philosophy began in the 17th century with René Descartes, Blaise Pascal and Nicolas Malebranche.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Descartes was the first Western philosopher since ancient times to attempt to build a philosophical system from the ground up rather than building on the work of predecessors.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Major philosophical contributions in the 18th century included Voltaire, who came to embody the Enlightenment, and Jean-Jacques Rousseau, whose work highly influenced the French Revolution.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] French philosophers made major contributions to the field in the 20th century including the existentialist works of Simone de Beauvoir, Camus, and Sartre.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Other influential contributors include the moral and political works of Simone Weil, contributions to structuralism including from Claude Lévi-Strauss and the post-structuralist works by Michel Foucault.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] French music experienced a golden age in the 17th century thanks to Louis XIV, who employed talented musicians and composers in the royal court.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Composers of this period include Marc-Antoine Charpentier, François Couperin, Michel-Richard Delalande, Jean-Baptiste Lully and Marin Marais, all of them composers at the court.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] After the death of Louis XIV, French musical creation lost dynamism, but in the next century the music of Jean-Philippe Rameau achieved some prestige.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Rameau became the dominant composer of French opera and the leading French composer of the harpsichord.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In the field of classical music, France has produced notable composers such as Gabriel Fauré, Claude Debussy, Maurice Ravel, and Hector Berlioz.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Debussy and Ravel are the most prominent figures associated with Impressionist music.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The two composers invented new musical forms and new sounds.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Debussy was among the most influential composers of the late 19th and early 20th centuries, and his use of non-traditional scales and chromaticism influenced many composers who followed.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] His music is noted for its sensory content and frequent usage of atonality.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Erik Satie was a key member of the early-20th-century Parisian avant-garde.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Francis Poulenc's best-known works are his piano suite *Trois mouvements perpétuels* (1919), the ballet *Les Biches* (1923), the *Concert champêtre* (1928) for harpsichord and orchestra, the opera *Dialogues des Carmélites* (1957) and the *Gloria* (1959) for soprano, choir and orchestra.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In the middle of the 20th century, Maurice Ohana, Pierre Schaeffer and Pierre Boulez contributed to the evolution of contemporary classical music.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] French music then followed the rapid emergence of pop and rock music in the middle of the 20th century.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Although English-speaking creations achieved popularity in the country, French pop music, known as *chanson française*, has also remained very popular.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Among the most important French artists of the century are Édith Piaf, Georges Brassens, Léo Ferré, Charles Aznavour and Serge Gainsbourg.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Modern pop music has seen the rise of popular French hip hop, French rock, techno/funk, and turntablists/DJs.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Although there are very few rock bands in France compared to English-speaking countries, bands such as Noir Désir, Mano Negra, Niagara, Les Rita Mitsouko and more recently Superbus, Phoenix and Gojira, or Shaka Ponk, have reached worldwide popularity.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France has historical and strong links with cinema, with two Frenchmen, Auguste and Louis Lumière (known as the Lumière Brothers) credited with creating cinema in 1895.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The world's first female filmmaker, Alice Guy-Blaché, was also from France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Several important cinematic movements, including the late 1950s and 1960s Nouvelle Vague, began in the country.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] It is noted for having a strong film industry, due in part to protections afforded by the government.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France remains a leader in filmmaking, as of 2015 producing more films than any other European country.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The nation also hosts the Cannes Festival, one of the most important and famous film festivals in the world.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Apart from its strong and innovative film tradition, France has also been a gathering spot for artists from across Europe and the world.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] For this reason, French cinema is sometimes intertwined with the cinema of foreign nations.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Directors from nations such as Poland (Roman Polanski, Krzysztof Kieślowski, Andrzej Żuławski), Argentina (Gaspar Noé, Edgardo Cozarinsky), Russia (Alexandre Alexeieff, Anatole Litvak), Austria (Michael Haneke) and Georgia (Géla Babluani, Otar Iosseliani) are prominent in the ranks of French cinema.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Conversely, French directors have had prolific and influential careers in other countries, such as Luc Besson, Jacques Tourneur or Francis Veber in the United States.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Although the French film market is dominated by Hollywood, France is the only nation in the world where American films make up the smallest share of total film revenues, at 50%, compared with 77% in Germany and 69% in Japan.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] French films account for 35% of the total film revenues of France, which is the highest percentage of national film revenues in the developed world outside the United States, compared to 14% in Spain and 8% in the UK.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 2013, France was the second-largest exporter of films in the world, after the United States.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] As part of its advocacy of cultural exception, a political concept of treating culture differently from other commercial products, France succeeded in convincing all EU members to refuse to include culture and audiovisuals in the list of liberalised sectors of the WTO in 1993.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] This decision was confirmed in a vote by UNESCO in 2005.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Fashion has been an important industry and cultural export of France since the 17th century, and modern "haute couture" originated in Paris in the 1860s.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Today, Paris, along with London, Milan, and New York City, is considered one of the world's fashion capitals, and the city is home or headquarters to many of the premier fashion houses.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The expression Haute couture is, in France, a legally protected name, guaranteeing certain quality standards.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The association of France with fashion and style (French: *la mode*) dates largely to the reign of Louis XIV.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France renewed its dominance of the high fashion (French: *couture or haute couture*) industry in the years 1860–1960 through the establishment of the great couturier houses such as Chanel, Dior, and Givenchy.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The French perfume industry is the world leader in its sector and is centred on the town of Grasse.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] According to 2017 data compiled by Deloitte, Louis Vuitton Moet Hennessey (LVMH), a French brand, is the largest luxury company in the world by sales, selling more than twice the amount of its nearest competitor.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Moreover, France also possesses 3 of the top 10 luxury goods companies by sales (LVMH, Kering SA, L'Oréal), more than any other country in the world.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 2021, regional daily newspapers, such as *Ouest-France*, *Sud Ouest*, *La Voix du Nord*, *Dauphiné Libéré*, *Le Télégramme*, and *Le Progrès*, more than doubled the sales of national newspapers, such as *Le Monde*, *Le Figaro*, *L'Équipe* (sports), *Le Parisien*, and *Les Echos* (finance).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Free dailies, distributed in metropolitan centres, continue to increase their market share.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The sector of weekly magazines includes more than 400 specialised weekly magazines published in the country.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Influential weeklies also include investigative and satirical papers *Le Canard Enchaîné* and *Charlie Hebdo*, as well as *Paris Match*.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] As in most industrialised nations, the print media have been affected by a severe crisis with the rise of the internet.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 2008, the government launched a major initiative to help the sector reform and become financially independent, but in 2009 it had to give €600,000 to help the print media cope with the 2008 financial crisis, in addition to existing subsidies.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In 1974, after years of centralised monopoly on radio and television, the governmental agency ORTF was split into several national institutions, but the three already-existing TV channels and four national radio stations remained under state control.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] It was only in 1981 that the government allowed free broadcasting in the territory.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Some consider hate speech laws in France to be too broad or severe, undermining freedom of speech.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Different regions have different styles.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In the north, butter and cream are common ingredients, whereas olive oil is more commonly used in the south.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Each region of France has traditional specialties: cassoulet in the southwest, choucroute in Alsace, quiche in the Lorraine region, beef bourguignon in Burgundy, Provençal tapenade, etc.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France is most famous for its wines and cheeses, which are often named for the territory where they are produced (AOC).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] A meal typically consists of three courses, *entrée* ('starter'), *plat principal* ('main course'), and *fromage* ('cheese') or *dessert*, sometimes with a salad served before the cheese or dessert.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] French cuisine is also regarded as a key element of the quality of life and the attractiveness of France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] A French publication, the *Michelin Guide*, awards *Michelin stars* for excellence to a select few establishments.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The acquisition or loss of a star can have dramatic effects on the success of a restaurant.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] By 2006, the *Michelin Guide* had awarded 620 stars to French restaurants.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] In addition to its wine tradition, France is also a major producer of beer and rum.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The three main French brewing regions are Alsace (60% of national production), Nord-Pas-de-Calais, and Lorraine.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] French rum is made in distilleries on islands in the Atlantic and Indian oceans.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France hosts "the world's biggest annual sporting event", the annual cycling race Tour de France.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Other popular sports played in France include football, judo, tennis, rugby union and pétanque.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France has hosted events such as the 1938 and 1998 FIFA World Cups, the 2007 Rugby World Cup, and the 2023 Rugby World Cup.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The country also hosted the 1960 European Nations' Cup, UEFA Euro 1984, UEFA Euro 2016 and 2019 FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] The Stade de France in Saint-Denis is France's largest stadium and was the venue for the 1998 FIFA World Cup and 2007 Rugby World Cup finals.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Since 1923, France is famous for its 24 Hours of Le Mans sports car endurance race.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Several major tennis tournaments take place in France, including the Paris Masters and the French Open, one of the four Grand Slam tournaments.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] French martial arts include Savate and Fencing.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France has a close association with the Modern Olympic Games; it was a French aristocrat, Baron Pierre de Coubertin, who suggested the Games' revival, at the end of the 19th century.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Paris hosted the second Games in 1900, and has hosted the Olympics on five further occasions: the 1924 Summer Olympics, the 2024 Summer Olympics both in Paris and three Winter Games (1924 in Chamonix, 1968 in Grenoble and 1992 in Albertville).
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] France introduced Olympics for deaf people (Deaflympics) in 1924.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Both the national football team and the national rugby union team are nicknamed "*Les Bleus*".
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Football is the most popular sport in France, with over 1,800,000 registered players and over 18,000 registered clubs.
[src:ballon-au-poing/france-p02] Rugby union is popular, particularly in Paris and the southwest of France.
